\ie
\c 1
\s1 The arrival of the true light
\p
\v 1 In the beginning was the message,\f + \fr 1:1 \ft TD: This passage is complex to translate because the message was also the messenger—that is, Yeshua came not only to teach about getting saved, but also to become the actual way to be saved!\f* and the message was with God, and the message was \add and is\add* God.
\v 2 He, \add the message\add*, was with \nd God\nd* \add even\add* at the creation \add of the universe\add*.
\v 3 Everything came into existence through the messenger\f + \fr 1:3 \ft Lit. him.\f*—\add there’s not even one thing that came into existence that wasn’t made by\add* him.
\v 4 He holds life, and that life is the light of humankind.
\v 5 And that light is shining in the darkness, and darkness cannot overcome him.
\p
\v 6 \x + \xo 1:6: \xt Mat 3:1; Mrk 1:4; Luk 3:1-2.\x*A man arrived who had been sent by \nd God\nd*. His name was Yohan.
\v 7 He came as a testimony to tell about the light so that everyone would believe the light.
\v 8 Yohan himself wasn’t the light—he was merely the announcer of the light.
\v 9 The true light which enlightens every person was coming into the world.
\p
\v 10 He was in the world and he’s the creator of the world, and yet the world didn’t even know him.
\v 11 He came to his own chosen people, but they wouldn’t accept him,
\v 12 however anyone who would accept him and trusted in his authority, he gave them the right to become children of \nd God\nd*—
\v 13 not physical children and not coming from human actions, but children of \nd God\nd*.
\p
\v 14 And the message became a human and lived here among us and we saw his greatness—the greatness of an only child of the father—full of grace and truth.
\p
\v 15 Yohan explained about him and loudly told everyone, “This is the one I meant when I said, ‘There’s someone coming after me, yet who came before me, because he existed before I did!’ ”
\p
\v 16 Because he has so much, we all received grace and then even more grace.
\v 17 The commandments came to us through Mosheh, but grace and truth came to us through \nd Yeshua\nd* the \nd messiah\nd*.
\v 18 No one has ever actually seen God, but the human son born from God the father and in close touch with him, he was the one to explain God to us.
\s1 The interrogation of Yohan-the-immerser
\r (Mat. 3:1-12; Mark 1:1-8; Luke 3:1-18)
\p
\v 19 Yohan explained some of this when the Jewish leaders sent out priests and temple workers from Yerushalem to ask him, “Who are you?”
\p
\v 20 He didn’t flinch from the truth and so he told them, “I am not the \nd chosen messiah\nd*.”
\p
\v 21 \x + \xo 1:21: a \xt Mal 4:5; \xo b \xt Deu 18:15,18.\x*So they asked him again, “Are you Eliyyah come back to life?”
\p And he answered, “No, I’m not.”
\p They asked, “Are you the prophet?”
\p Again he answered, “No, I’m not.”
\p
\v 22 So they asked him, “Who are you then? We need to give an answer to the ones who sent us. How do you describe yourself?”
\p
\v 23 \x + \xo 1:23: \xt Isa 40:3 (LXX).\x*So he said, “I am a voice shouting\f + \fr 1:23 \ft We’ve deliberately omitted putting a comma here, because it’s also possible that the comma should go after ‘wilderness’.\f* in the wilderness smooth the path of the \nd master\nd*, as the prophet Isayah said.”
\p
\v 24 Some of the ones sent out were members of the Pharisee party.
\v 25 These ones asked Yohan, “So why are you immersing people then if you aren’t the \nd messiah\nd* or Eliyyah or the prophet?”
\p
\v 26 He answered, “I’m immersing people in water, but somewhere here among us all there’s someone you don’t know—
\v 27 the one coming after me, and I’m not even good enough to untie his sandal straps!”
\p
\v 28 All this happened in Bethany on the east side of the Yordan River where Yohan was immersing people.
\s1 Yeshua gets publicly revealed
\p
\v 29 The next day Yohan saw \nd Yeshua\nd* coming towards him, and said, “Hey! Here’s the sacrificial lamb of \nd God\nd* who’s come to take away the sin of the world.
\v 30 This is the man I was talking about when I said, ‘There’s someone coming after me, yet who came before me, because he existed before I did.’
\v 31 I didn’t know who he was but nevertheless I came and immersed people in water so that this man could be revealed to \add all\add* Israel.”
\p
\v 32 And Yohan further explained, “I saw God’s \nd spirit\nd* come down and settle on him.
\v 33 I didn’t know which one was him, but the one who sent me to immerse people in water said, ‘When you see the spirit coming down and settling on someone, he is the one who will immerse people with God’s holy spirit.’
\v 34 And I have seen that, and so I can assure you that he is God’s son.”
\s1 Yeshua gets a few followers
\p
\v 35 The next day, Yohan was back there with two of his apprentices
\v 36 and noticing \nd Yeshua\nd* walking nearby he said, “Look! There’s the \add sacrificial\add* lamb of \nd God\nd*.”
\p
\v 37 When his two apprentices heard him say that, they left him and followed \nd Yeshua\nd*.
\v 38 But \nd Yeshua\nd* turned and saw them following him, and asked them, “\wj What do you two want?\wj*”
\p And they said to him, “Teacher, where do you live?”
\p
\v 39 “\wj Come and see,\wj*” Yeshua replied. So they went with him and saw where he lived, and then they stayed there that night, because it was already late afternoon.
\p
\v 40 Andrew, the brother of Simon Peter was one of those two who heard Yohan and then followed Yeshua.
\v 41 As soon as he found his brother, he said to Simon, “We have found the messiah—God’s chosen one,”
\v 42 and led him to Yeshua. When Yeshua saw him, he said, “\wj Ah, you are Simon, Yohan’s son, but from now on you’ll be called Peter which means \it stone\it*.\wj*”
\s1 Philip and Nathanael join the group
\p
\v 43 The following day, \nd Yeshua\nd* wanted to go to Galilee. He found Philip and told him, “\wj Follow me!\wj*”
\v 44 Philip was from the town of Bethsaida where Andrew and Peter lived.
\v 45 Philip then found \nd Nathanael\nd* and told him, “We’ve found the one that Mosheh and the prophets wrote about in the Scriptures. He’s \nd Yeshua\nd* from \nd Nazareth\nd*.”
\p
\v 46 And \nd Nathanael\nd* said, “Does anything good come from \nd Nazareth\nd*?”
\p So Philip answered, “Well, come and see \add for yourself\add*.”
\p
\v 47 \nd Yeshua\nd* saw \nd Nathanael\nd* approaching and said, “\wj Ah, this is an honest Israeli.\wj*”
\p
\v 48 But \nd Nathanael\nd* queried him, “Where do you know \em me\em* from?”
\p And \nd Yeshua\nd* replied, “\wj Actually I saw you under that fig tree before Philip had even called you.\wj*”
\p
\v 49 \nd Nathanael\nd* exclaimed, “Great teacher! You \em are\em* God’s son! You’re the king of Israel!”
\p
\v 50 \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “\wj So you believe this because I said that I had seen you under the fig tree. You’ll get to see much greater things than that!\wj*”
\v 51 \x + \xo 1:51: \xt Gen 28:12.\x*And he continued, “\wj Honestly, I’m telling all of you: you’ll be seeing the sky opened up and God’s messengers going up and coming down on me—humanity’s child.\wj*”
\c 2
\s1 The wine miracle
\p
\v 1 On the Tuesday\f + \fr 2:1 \ft Or possibly, ‘Three days later’.\f*, there was a wedding in Cana in Galilee, and \nd Yeshua’s\nd* mother was there
\v 2 and \nd Yeshua\nd* and his apprentices were also invited.
\v 3 When the wine ran out at the wedding, his mother said to him, “They haven’t got any more wine.”
\p
\v 4 \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj What does that have to do with us, mother? It’s not the time for my ministry yet.\wj*”
\p
\v 5 But his mother told the servants, “Just do whatever he tells you.”
\p
\v 6 Now there were six empty stone water jars there that are used for Jewish purification ceremonies. (Each one could hold over 70 litres.)
\v 7 So \nd Yeshua\nd* told them to fill the jars with water, and they filled them up.
\v 8 Then he said, “\wj Okay, now take a sample out and give it to the MC.\wj*” So they took some
\v 9 and when the MC tasted the water that had now turned to wine, not knowing where it had come from he called the groom
\v 10 and exclaimed, “Most people supply the best wine at the beginning \add of the reception\add*, and the cheaper stuff when people are a bit tipsy. But you’ve kept the best wine until last!”
\p
\v 11 This event in Cana, Galilee, was the first of the miracles that \nd Yeshua\nd* did, and it revealed his greatness and his followers believed that he was from God.
\p
\v 12 \x + \xo 2:12: \xt Mat 4:13.\x*After that, Yeshua and his mother and brothers and his followers travelled east to Capernaum, but they only stayed there a few days.
\s1 Yeshua disturbs the temple traders
\r (Mat. 21:12-13; Mark 11:15-17; Luke 19:45-46)
\p
\v 13 \x + \xo 2:13: \xt Exo 12:1-27.\x*By then it was getting close to the time of the Jewish Festival of the Passover, and \nd Yeshua\nd* went down to Yerushalem.
\v 14 There in the temple, he discovered merchants selling cows and sheep and doves, and moneychangers sitting at their tables.
\v 15 Yeshua formed some cords into a whip and drove the sheep and cows out of the temple grounds, and he overturned the tables—spilling the coins of the moneychangers onto the ground.
\v 16 He scolded the ones selling doves, saying, “\wj Get them out of here! Don’t be making my father’s house into a market.\wj*”
\v 17 \x + \xo 2:17: \xt Psa 69:9.\x*That reminded his followers of the scripture: “I’ll be filled with zeal for your temple.”
\p
\v 18 Then the Jewish leaders responded, “Do a miracle to show that you have the authority to do these things.”
\p
\v 19 \x + \xo 2:19: \xt Mat 26:61; 27:40; Mrk 14:58; 15:29.\x*But \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj Well, destroy this temple and I’ll raise\f + \fr 2:19 \ft We couldn’t easily use \em rebuild\em* here because there’s a play on words—see verse 21.\f* it again in three days.\wj*”
\p
\v 20 The leaders smirked, “This temple took forty-six years to build, and you reckon that you can raise it again in three days?”
\p
\v 21 But Yeshua had been meaning his own body when he was talking about the temple.
\v 22 In the future when he was actually raised from the dead, his followers remembered this statement, and they believed both the \add Hebrew\add* scriptures and \nd Yeshua’s\nd* message.
\s1 Yeshua does miracles and knows thoughts
\p
\v 23 When Yeshua was at the Passover Feast in Yerushalem, many believed in his authority because they saw the miracles that he was able to do.
\v 24 But \nd Yeshua\nd* never fully entrusted himself to them, because he knew what people are like.
\v 25 (He didn’t need anyone to tell him what people are like because he could see what any person was like on the inside.)
\c 3
\s1 Yeshua tells Nicodemus about the need to be reborn
\p
\v 1 After dark one evening, a Jewish leader named Nicodemus who was a member of the Pharisee party
\v 2 went to Yeshua and said, “Teacher, we know that God has sent you as a teacher, because no one could do these kinds of miracles if God wasn’t with him.”
\p
\v 3 \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “\wj I’ll tell you frankly that no one can enter God’s kingdom unless he is reborn.\wj*”
\p
\v 4 Nicodemus questioned, “How can an adult be reborn? A person can’t just return to their mother’s womb and then get born a second time!”
\p
\v 5 But \nd Yeshua\nd* continued, “\wj Honestly, I’m telling you: unless a person is born from both water \em and\em* the \nd spirit\nd*, they can’t enter God’s kingdom.\wj*
\v 6 \wj Someone that’s born from a body is flesh \add and bone\add*, but someone that’s born from God’s spirit is spiritual.\wj*
\v 7 \wj So you shouldn’t be surprised that I told you that everyone needs to be reborn.\wj*
\v 8 \wj The wind blows wherever it wants, and you can hear its sound but you can’t actually see where it’s coming from and where it’s going to. So too with everyone who’s born from God’s spirit.\wj*”
\p
\v 9 Nicodemus replied, “How can all this even happen?”
\p
\v 10 “\wj You’re a Jewish teacher,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj and yet you don’t know all this?\wj*
\v 11 \wj It’s true that we just teach what we know, and explain what we’ve seen ourselves, but you people aren’t accepting our testimony.\wj*
\v 12 \wj If I tell all of you earthly things and you don’t believe them, how will you ever believe if I explain \em heavenly\em* things?\wj*
\v 13 \wj None of you have gone up into heaven, but I, humanity’s child, have come down from heaven.\wj*
\p
\v 14 \x + \xo 3:14: \xt Num 21:9.\x*“\wj Just like Mosheh lifted up that \add bronze\add* snake \add on a pole\add* in the wilderness, it’s \add also\add* necessary for humanity’s child to be lifted up,\wj*\f + \fr 3:14 \ft lifted up / exalted: See https://bibleDifferences.net/2019/04/25/156-exulted\f*
\v 15 \wj so that everyone who believes in him won’t die, but will live forever.\wj*\f + \fr 3:15 \ft See http://bibleandtech.blogspot.com/2021/03/john-314-21-translation-and-commentary.html\f*
\v 16 \wj Because in that same way, \nd God\nd* loves \add the people of\add* the world enough to cause \add his\add* only son to be born and to give him to the world, so that everyone who believes this will not die, but will \add go on to\add* live forever.\wj*
\p
\v 17 “\wj \nd God\nd* didn’t send his son here to condemn people, but rather to save them.\wj*
\v 18 \wj Anyone who trusts in me will not be condemned. However, anyone who doesn’t believe this has already been condemned because he rejected the authority of the only son that \nd God\nd* fathered.\wj*
\v 19 \wj And this is the verdict: that light has come into the world, but some people love the darkness more than the light because they do evil things,\wj*
\v 20 \wj because everyone who does evil things hates the light and doesn’t come to the light so that their actions won’t be exposed.\wj*
\v 21 \wj But anyone who does what is right, comes toward the light so that their actions can be revealed as being done with God’s help.\wj*”
\s1 Yohan approves of Yeshua’s popularity
\p
\v 22 After this, \nd Yeshua\nd* and his followers went down to Yudea, and stayed there and immersed some believers.
\v 23 Yohan was also immersing people at Aenon near Salim because there was plenty of water there and people would come \add to him\add* to get immersed.
\v 24 \x + \xo 3:24: \xt Mat 14:3; Mrk 6:17; Luk 3:19-20.\x*(At this point in time, Yohan had not yet been put in prison.)
\v 25 Then a debate about purification started between Yohan’s followers and a religious leader.\f + \fr 3:25 \ft https://www.billmounce.com/monday-with-mounce/what-does-the-word-%E2%80%9Cjew%E2%80%9D-mean-you-john-3-25\f*
\v 26 So some people went to Yohan and said, “Teacher, that man that came to you across the river and that you testified about, now \em he’s\em* immersing people and so they’re all going to him.”
\p
\v 27 “None of us get anything if it’s not being given from heaven,” Yohan answered.
\v 28 \x + \xo 3:28: \xt Yhn 1:20.\x*“You yourselves know that I said that I’m not the \nd messiah\nd*, but rather the one coming before him.
\v 29 It’s the groom that has the bride—the best man is happy because he sees that the groom is happy. So I’m actually completely happy with all this.
\v 30 It’s right and proper that he should increase and I should fade out.”
\p
\v 31 “The one who came down from heaven is greater than any of us. We came from this world and speak in our earthly ways. The one who came down from heaven is greater than any of us.
\v 32 He explains about what he’s seen and heard, but people don’t believe him.
\v 33 Anyone who does believe him, confirms that \nd God\nd* is true.
\v 34 The one that God sent tells us God’s words, because God doesn’t ration his \nd spirit\nd*.
\v 35 \x + \xo 3:35: \xt Mat 11:27; Luk 10:22.\x*The father loves the son and has put him in charge of everything.
\v 36 Anyone who believes \add God’s\add* son will live forever, but anyone who disobeys the son won’t be seeing life, but will feel God’s severe anger \add instead\add*.”
\c 4
\s1 Yeshua chats with a woman at the well
\p
\v 1 When \nd Yeshua\nd* found out that the Pharisee party knew that he was gaining and immersing more followers than Yohan had,
\v 2 (although actually it wasn’t \nd Yeshua\nd* himself that was immersing them, but his trainees that were doing it),
\v 3 he left Yudea and went back up to Galilee.
\v 4 On the way up, he decided to go through Samaria \add (Heb. Shomron)\add*.
\p
\v 5 \x + \xo 4:5: \xt Gen 33:19; Josh 24:32.\x*By choosing that route, they came to a town in Samaria called Sukar, which was near the place that the \add patriarch\add* Yosef had inherited from his father Yacob,
\v 6 and Yacob’s well was there. \nd Yeshua\nd* was tired from all the walking and was sitting by the well around midday.
\p
\v 7 A woman came from the town to get water from the well, and \nd Yeshua\nd* asked her for a drink
\v 8 since his followers had gone into the town to buy some lunch.
\p
\v 9 \x + \xo 4:9: \xt Est 4:1-5; Neh 4:1-2.\x*The woman said to him, “You’re a Jew. How come you’re asking me for a drink when I’m from Samaria?” (Jews don’t normally associate with anyone from Samaria.)
\p
\v 10 \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj If you had recognised God’s gift and who it is who’s asking you for a drink, you would have asked me and I would have given you \em living\em* water \add to drink\add*.\wj*”
\p
\v 11 But the woman countered, “Mister, you don’t even have \add rope and\add* a bucket to reach the water in the deep well. How then could you get ‘living water’?
\v 12 I doubt that you’re greater than our ancestor Yacob who made this well for us and drank this water along with his children and his animals.”
\p
\v 13 \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “\wj Everyone who drinks this water will get thirsty again,\wj*
\v 14 \wj but whoever drinks the water that I give them will find a well springing up inside them—springing into eternal life.\wj*”
\p
\v 15 So the woman said, “Okay, then. Give me some of that water so that I won’t get thirsty and won’t have to keep coming out here to the well.”
\p
\v 16 Yeshua said, “\wj First, go and get your husband and return here.\wj*”
\p
\v 17 “I don’t have a husband!” she retorted.
\p “\wj True enough—indeed you don’t,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* said.
\v 18 “\wj You’ve had five husbands and you’re not married to the man you’re living with, so that was true.\wj*”
\p
\v 19 “Mister, I can see that you’re a prophet,” the woman reacted.
\v 20 “Our ancestors worshipped on this mountain, but you Jews claim that people should only worship there in Yerushalem.”
\p
\v 21 Then \nd Yeshua\nd* told her, “\wj You need to believe that I was sent from God, woman, because a day is coming when everyone will be worshipping him neither on this mountain, nor in Yerushalem.\wj*
\v 22 \wj You people in Samaria don’t even know who you worship, but we do, because people will be saved by means of us Jews.\wj*
\v 23 \wj But a time is coming, starting even now, when the true worshippers will be worshipping the father in spirit and truth, because those are the ones that he is wanting to worship him.\wj*
\v 24 \wj \nd God\nd* is spirit, and the ones worshipping him must worship in spirit and total honesty.\wj*”
\p
\v 25 The woman said, “I’m aware that the messiah is coming—the chosen one of God. Whenever he appears, he’ll teach us everything.”
\p
\v 26 “\wj \em I am\em* the messiah,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* responded. “\wj Yes, he’s speaking to you!\wj*”
\p
\v 27 After this, his followers arrived back, and they were astounded that he was speaking with a woman. However no one dared ask her, “What are you after?” Or to ask him, “Why are you talking with her?”
\p
\v 28 So the woman left her water jar there, and went back into the town where she told the people,
\v 29 “Come and see a man who knew as much about me as I know myself! He must be the \nd messiah\nd*!”
\v 30 So they went out from the town to go and see Yeshua.
\p
\v 31 Meanwhile, Yeshua’s followers encouraged him, “Teacher, here, eat.”
\p
\v 32 But he said, “\wj I’ve had food to eat that you don’t know about.\wj*”
\p
\v 33 This made his followers ask each other, “Did you see anyone bring him something to eat?”
\p
\v 34 “\wj Obeying God who sent me is like food to me, and I plan to finish his work,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* explained.
\v 35 “\wj Don’t you all have a saying about needing to wait four months for a harvest? But I’m telling you that you all should open your eyes and look at the fields, because they’re already lightening up as harvest time approaches.\wj*
\v 36 \wj The harvester gets paid with a harvest that will last forever so that the ones who plant and the ones who harvest can all celebrate.\wj*
\v 37 \wj There’s truth in the statement that one person plants and a different person harvests.\wj*
\v 38 \wj I’ve sent you all out to harvest where you haven’t worked before—others did the groundwork and you benefit from their work.\wj*”
\p
\v 39 And many people of Samaria came out of that town and believed that Yeshua is God because the woman had told them that he knew everything about her.
\v 40 So when they all came, they asked him to stay in their town and they stayed on there for a couple of days.
\p
\v 41 As a result of his teaching, many more believed
\v 42 so then they told the woman, “We no longer believe just because of what you said, but now that we’ve heard him for ourselves, we can see that he really is the saviour of the world.”
\s1 Yeshua heals the official’s son
\p
\v 43 After his two days in Samaria, Yeshua continued on up to Galilee.
\v 44 \x + \xo 4:44: \xt Mat 13:57; Mrk 6:4; Luk 4:24.\x*\nd He\nd* himself had told them that no prophet gets honoured in his own home town.
\v 45 \x + \xo 4:45: \xt Yhn 2:23.\x*When he got to Galilee, the people accepted him, having seen everything that he’d done at the feast in Yerushalem because they had also been down there.
\p
\v 46 \x + \xo 4:46: \xt Yhn 2:1-11.\x*So he went again to Cana there in Galilee where he had made the water into wine. Now there was a royal official there, whose son in Capernaum was ill.
\v 47 When the official heard that \nd Yeshua\nd* was coming up from Yudea to Galilee, he went and asked him if he would come and heal his son who was dying.
\v 48 \nd Yeshua\nd* said to him, “\wj You people won’t believe unless you see miracles and other marvels.\wj*”
\p
\v 49 But the official begged him, “Sir, please come before my child dies.”
\p
\v 50 “\wj Go back there and see,\wj*” Yeshua responded. “\wj Your son will recover.\wj*”
\p The man believed what Yeshua had told him, and so he started off.
\v 51 On his way, his slaves met him and reported that the boy was alive and well.
\p
\v 52 So the official asked them what time it was that he got better, and they replied that the fever had subsided around 1pm.
\v 53 The father knew that that was the time when Yeshua had told him that his son would recover, and as a result his whole household believed \add that Yeshua came from God\add*.
\p
\v 54 This was the second miracle that \nd Yeshua\nd* did after leaving Yudea and going to Galilee.
\c 5
\s1 Yeshua heals a man at the pool
\p
\v 1 After all this, there was another Jewish feast, so \nd Yeshua\nd* went down to Yerushalem.
\v 2 In Yerushalem at the Sheep Gate, there’s the Bethsaida pool that has five alcoves
\v 3 and a large number of sick, blind, lame, and paralysed people lie there in them.
\v 4 ◘
\v 5 One man had been there for thirty-eight years,
\v 6 and when \nd Yeshua\nd* noticed him and knew that he’d been there for so long, he asked, “\wj Do you want to get better?\wj*”
\p
\v 7 “Yes mister,” the sick man answered, “but when the water starts moving, I don’t have a companion to lift me into the pool, so someone else always get there before me.”
\p
\v 8 Then \nd Yeshua\nd* said, “\wj Stand up and pick up your bedroll and start walking.\wj*”
\v 9 The man immediately stood up, picked up his gear, and started to walk.
\p However, this was the weekly rest day.
\v 10 \x + \xo 5:10: \xt Neh 13:19; Jer 17:21.\x*So the religious leaders said to the man, “Hey! It’s against the law for you to carry your bedding on the rest day!”
\p
\v 11 But the man answered, “The man who made me better told me to pick up my bedroll and start walking.”
\p
\v 12 “Oh. Who was it that told you to take that stuff and start walking?”
\p
\v 13 But the man who had been healed didn’t even know who it was, because \nd Yeshua\nd* had quickly left when a crowd had formed.
\p
\v 14 Later on, \nd Yeshua\nd* found the man in the temple and told him, “\wj Look, you’re better now so don’t go on sinning, because you don’t want anything worse to happen to you.\wj*”
\p
\v 15 The man then went and told the leaders that it was \nd Yeshua\nd* who had made him better.
\v 16 As a result, the leaders started harassing \nd Yeshua\nd* because he had done this on a rest day.
\v 17 But Yeshua just replied, “\wj My father is working today, and so I’m also working.\wj*”
\p
\v 18 Because of this, the leaders became determined that he must be put to death—not just because he broke the rules for the rest day, but most of all because he was calling God his own father, thus making himself equal to God!
\s1 Authority over life is given to the son
\p
\v 19 So \nd Yeshua\nd* responded to them, “\wj I want to tell you all something: The son can’t initiate anything by himself. He can only do what he sees his father doing, because whatever his father is doing, he also does things like that.\wj*
\v 20 \wj You see, the father loves his son and shows him everything that he’s doing. In fact, he’ll be showing him even greater things than what he’s done already, so that you all will be amazed.\wj*
\v 21 \wj Because the father brings the dead back to life, giving them new life, so too the son can give life to anyone who he wants.\wj*
\v 22 \wj The father won’t be judging anyone, but has already given that task to the son,\wj*
\v 23 \wj so that the people might honour the son like they honour the father. But anyone who is not honouring the son, is also dishonouring the father who sent him.\wj*
\p
\v 24 “\wj I assure you that anyone who hears my message and believes that I was sent by God, will live forever and will not be condemned, but has moved from death into life.\wj*
\v 25 \wj I can also assure you that a time is coming, and in fact is here already, when the dead will be hearing the voice of God’s son and that voice will bring them back to life.\wj*
\v 26 \wj As the father is the source of life, he gave the power of giving life to the son\wj*
\v 27 \wj and gave him the authority to be the final judge, because he is humanity’s child.\wj*
\v 28 \wj Don’t be surprised at this, because a time is coming when everyone in their graves will be hearing his voice,\wj*
\v 29 \x + \xo 5:29: \xt Dan 12:2.\x*\wj and the ones having done what is good will be given new life, and the ones having done what is evil will be condemned.\wj*”
\s1 The unbelief of the religious leaders
\p
\v 30 Yeshua continued explaining to the religious leaders, “\wj I don’t do anything in isolation. Whenever I hear from him, only then do I judge and my judgement is correct and impartial because I’m not imposing \em my\em* desires, but the desire of the one who sent me.\wj*
\p
\v 31 “\wj If I just testified about myself, my testimony would not be correct or even valid.\wj*
\v 32 \wj However it’s another one that’s testifying about me, and I know that his testimony about me is true.\wj*
\v 33 \x + \xo 5:33: \xt Yhn 1:19-27; 3:27-30.\x*\wj You sent people out to question Yohan and his testimony was true.\wj*
\v 34 \wj but I don’t even need any testimony that comes from people, because I am teaching you how to be saved.\wj*
\v 35 \wj Yohan was a bright and shining light and you appreciated it for a short time.\wj*
\v 36 \wj But I have a stronger testimony than Yohan’s because the father has entrusted works to me to complete, and which I’m already doing and which clearly show that the father sent me here.\wj*
\v 37 \x + \xo 5:37: \xt Mat 3:17; Mrk 1:11; Luk 3:22.\x*\wj And since he sent me, he himself has testified about me. You people have never listened to his voice, nor have you ever seen him!\wj*
\v 38 \wj And his way of thinking is obviously not in your minds, because you don’t believe the one that he sent.\wj*
\v 39 \wj You look in the Jewish scriptures because you suppose that they’ll lead you to eternal life. Those very scriptures testify about me coming,\wj*
\v 40 \wj yet you refuse to come to me in order to receive life.\wj*
\p
\v 41 “\wj I’m not getting any praise from people\wj*
\v 42 \wj but I do know that you people don’t actually love \nd God\nd* in your hearts.\wj*
\v 43 \wj I have come with my father’s authority and you don’t accept me, but if someone came claiming their own authority, you’d happily accept them.\wj*
\v 44 \wj How \em could\em* you possibly believe when you just accept acclamations from each other, but don’t even seek praise from the only \add \nd God\nd*\add*.\wj*
\v 45 \wj But don’t be assuming that I’ll be accusing you all in front of the father. No, the one who’ll accuse you is Mosheh because he’s the one that you’re hoping to please.\wj*
\v 46 \wj The trouble is that if you actually believed what Mosheh wrote, you would believe me, because Mosheh was writing about me.\wj*
\v 47 \wj But since you don’t really believe his writings, you’re not at all likely to believe me.\wj*”
\c 6
\s1 The feeding of 5,000 families
\r (Mat. 14:13-21; Mark 6:30-44; Luke 9:10-17)
\p
\v 1 After all this, \nd Yeshua\nd* crossed the lake \add in a boat\add*.\f + \fr 6:1 \ft Here Yohan also uses the Roman name “Lake Tiberias” rather than just “Lake Galilee”.\f*
\v 2 A large crowd followed him because they’d seen his miraculous healings of sick people.
\v 3 \nd Yeshua\nd* climbed a hill and sat there with his apprentices.
\v 4 At that time, it was getting close to the Jewish Festival of Passover.
\v 5 When \nd Yeshua\nd* looked out and saw the large crowd coming, he asked Philip, “\wj Where can we get enough food from to feed all this crowd?\wj*”
\v 6 But he was only saying this to test Philip because he already knew what he was going to do.
\p
\v 7 Philip answered, “To buy even just a snack for this many people would take several months’ wages!”
\p
\v 8 Now one of Yeshua’s apprentices, Simon Peter’s brother, Andrew, said to Yeshua,
\v 9 “There’s a young boy here with five buns and two \add small cooked\add* fish, but that wouldn’t even start to feed this crowd.”
\p
\v 10 But \nd Yeshua\nd* told them to get all the people to sit down as there was a large grassy area. So they all sat down—some five thousand men were counted.
\v 11 Then he took the buns and gave thanks to God, and started passing around both the buns and the fish, and everyone ate as much as they wanted.
\v 12 Once everyone was full, Yeshua got his apprentices to collect the leftover fragments so as not to waste anything.
\v 13 So they gathered the leftovers and filled twelve baskets with leftover bread.
\p
\v 14 The people who had witnessed this and other miracles said, “This really is the prophet that God promised to send!”
\v 15 But \nd Yeshua\nd* knew that they intended to come and grab him to proclaim him as their king, so he moved out of the crowd and on up the hill.
\s1 Yeshua comes walking across the lake
\r (Mat. 14:22-33; Mark 6:45-52)
\p
\v 16 As it moved into evening, Yeshua’s apprentices went back down to the lake
\v 17 and having boarded the boat, they set out across the lake toward Capernaum. By then it was dark, and there was still no sign of \nd Yeshua\nd*.
\v 18 Then a strong wind hit the lake and the water got rough.
\v 19 When they had rowed about five kilometres, they saw \nd Yeshua\nd* walking on top of the lake and approaching the boat, and they were very scared.
\v 20 But he told them, “\wj Don’t worry—it’s me.\wj*”
\v 21 After that they were willing to let him into the boat, and immediately the boat was at their arrival place.
\p
\v 22 The next day, the crowd looked across the lake and saw that only one small boat had crossed, and they knew that only \nd Yeshua’s\nd* apprentices had boarded that boat and left, and not Yeshua himself.
\v 23 Other boats came across from Tiberias near the place where they had eaten the bread after the \nd master\nd* had given thanks.
\v 24 So when all the people saw that Yeshua wasn’t around and his apprentices had left, they went off looking for Yeshua in Capernaum.
\s1 The bread that enables true life
\p
\v 25 When they found him there across the lake, they queried, “Teacher, how did you get here?”
\p
\v 26 “\wj Honestly, I know that you’re not looking for me because you saw \add God working\add* miracles,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj but because you all had plenty of food to fill you up.\wj*
\v 27 \wj Don’t \add just\add* work for the food which goes off, but for the food which lasts forever—the food which humanity’s child will give to you because \nd God\nd* the father has put his mark of approval on him.\wj*”
\p
\v 28 Puzzled, they asked him, “What should we be doing if we want to work for \nd God\nd*?”
\p
\v 29 He answered, “\wj Doing God’s work is putting your trust in the one that he sent here.\wj*”
\p
\v 30 “If so,” they said, “what miracle will you do for us to see so that we can believe that you \add came from God\add*? What can \em you\em* do?
\v 31 \x + \xo 6:31: \xt Exo 16:4,15; Psa 78:24.\x*Our ancestors ate the manna\f + \fr 6:31 \ft Manna was a word that meant ‘stuff’ and referred to some kind of flakes that regularly came down from the sky in the time of Mosheh and could be eaten as food.\f* out in the wilderness, just like Mosheh wrote, ‘He gave them bread from the sky to eat.’ ”
\p
\v 32 \nd Yeshua\nd* said to them, “\wj Actually I can tell you that it wasn’t Mosheh who gave them bread from heaven, but my father gives you the real bread from heaven,\wj*
\v 33 \wj because God’s bread is the one who came down from heaven and who gives life to the world.\wj*”
\p
\v 34 So they requested, “Mister, keep giving us that bread.”
\p
\v 35 “\wj \em I am\em* the bread that gives life,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj anyone who comes to me will never hunger, and the one believing in me, will never be thirsty again.\wj*
\v 36 \wj But as I said already, although you have seen me you refuse to believe me.\wj*
\v 37 \wj Everyone that the father gives to me will come to me, and I certainly won’t turn away anyone who comes to me,\wj*
\v 38 \wj because I came down from heaven, not to do what I want, but to do what the one who sent me wants.\wj*
\v 39 \wj And what he wants is for me to not lose anyone that he’s given to me, but to bring them back to life on the last day.\wj*
\v 40 \wj My father wants everyone who watches me and believes in me to live forever, because I will bring them back to life on that final day.\wj*”
\p
\v 41 This little speech made the religious leaders grumble about him because he had said that he was the food that came down from heaven,
\v 42 as they figured out, “This is \nd Yeshua\nd* the son of Yosef and so we know his parents. So how can he say that he came down from heaven?”
\p
\v 43 \nd Yeshua\nd* scolded them, “\wj Don’t be grumbling to each other.\wj*
\v 44 \wj No one can join me unless the father who sent me attracts them, and then I’ll be bringing them back to life on that final day.\wj*
\v 45 \x + \xo 6:45: \xt Isa 54:13.\x*\wj The prophets wrote that the people will be taught by \nd God\nd*. And everyone who’s heard and learned from the father comes to me.\wj*
\v 46 \wj Not that any person has seen the father—only the one who came from \nd God\nd* has seen him.\wj*
\v 47 \wj I tell you sincerely: anyone who believes \add in me\add* will live forever.\wj*
\v 48 \wj \em I am\em* the bread that gives true life.\wj*
\v 49 \wj Your ancestors ate manna in the wilderness, but they all went on to die.\wj*
\v 50 \wj But \em I am\em* the bread that came down from heaven and anyone who eats this will not die.\wj*
\v 51 \wj \em I am\em* the living bread that came down from heaven and if anyone eats this bread, he will live through to the next age.\wj*”
\p
\v 52 At this point, the religious leaders began to argue with each other, “How could this man give us his flesh to eat?”
\p
\v 53 So \nd Yeshua\nd* explained, “\wj Indeed if you don’t eat my flesh and drink my blood, you aren’t truly alive!\wj*
\v 54 \wj Anyone who eats my flesh and drinks my blood will gain eternal life—I will bring them back to life on that final day.\wj*
\v 55 \wj For my flesh is the true food, and my blood is the true drink.\wj*
\v 56 \wj Anyone who eats my flesh and drinks my blood lives in me, and I will live in him.\wj*
\v 57 \wj The father is alive and sent me here, and I am alive because of Him, so also the person who eats me will be alive because of me.\wj*
\v 58 \wj Unlike your ancestors who ate that bread \add from the sky\add* and then died, anyone who eats this bread that came down from heaven will live through to the next age.\wj*”
\s1 Many people find the teaching too difficult
\p
\v 59 Yeshua taught all of this in the meeting hall there in Capernaum.
\v 60 But even many of his followers who heard it said, “This is difficult teaching—it’s too hard to take.”
\p
\v 61 But \nd Yeshua\nd* already knew inside that his followers were grumbling about this and asked them, “\wj Do you find this offensive?\wj*
\v 62 \wj What if you were to see humanity’s child ascending to where he came from?\wj*
\v 63 \wj It’s the spirit that is the source of life, not the body. The concepts that I’ve taught you are all spiritual and life-giving.\wj*
\v 64 \wj But there are some here who don’t believe me.\wj*” Actually, \nd Yeshua\nd* had already known from the beginning just who would believe and which person would betray him
\v 65 so he said, “\wj That’s why I told you that no one can come to me unless the father has given them to me.\wj*”
\p
\v 66 After this, many of his followers went back and no longer accompanied him around.
\p
\v 67 So \nd Yeshua\nd* said to his twelve \add apprentices\add*, “\wj Don’t you want to leave as well?\wj*”
\p
\v 68 \x + \xo 6:68-69: \xt Mat 16:16; Mrk 8:29; Luk 9:20.\x*“\nd Master\nd*,” Simon answered, “if we went, who would we follow then? You’re the \add only\add* one who teaches about living forever.
\v 69 We believe and know that you are the holy son of \nd God\nd*.”
\p
\v 70 \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “\wj Didn’t I choose all twelve of you myself? And yet one of you is a devil.\wj*”
\v 71 (He was talking about Yudas, Simon Iscariot’s son, because he was the one who would go on to betray him.)
\c 7
\s1 Yeshua’s sceptical brothers dare him to go public
\p
\v 1 After all this, \nd Yeshua\nd* travelled around Galilee. (He didn’t want to travel around Yudea because the leaders there wanted to execute him.)
\v 2 \x + \xo 7:2: \xt Lev 23:34; Deu 16:13.\x*As it was now getting close to the Jewish Feast With Tents,
\v 3 his brothers said to him, “You should leave this place and go down to Yudea so that all your followers can see the miracles that you’re doing.
\v 4 If you want to become well-known, you don’t do things out of the main stream. If you want to do miracles, \add go and\add* show yourself to the wider world.
\v 5 (You see, not even Yeshua’s own \add half-\add*brothers believed \add that he came from God\add*.)
\p
\v 6 So \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “\wj Well, you guys can do that any time, but it’s not the right time for me yet.\wj*
\v 7 \wj All the people won’t hate you guys, but they do hate me because I teach about the evil things they are doing.\wj*
\v 8 \wj You all go on down to Yerushalem ahead of me. I’m not going to the feast yet because it’s not yet the right time for me.\wj*”
\v 9 After saying this, Yeshua stayed up in Galilee.
\s1 Yeshua starts teaching about authentic justice
\p
\v 10 But after his \add half-\add*brothers had left to go down to Yerushalem, Yeshua also went—not in the public limelight but just incognito so to speak.
\v 11 However at the celebrations, the Jewish religious leaders were searching for him, and were asking around where he was.
\p
\v 12 Even among the crowds there was a lot of quiet banter with some saying that Yeshua is a good man and others complaining that he was misleading the people.
\v 13 Either way, no one was speaking out in public about him, because they were afraid of the reaction of the religious leaders.
\p
\v 14 Finally sometime in the middle of the celebrations, \nd Yeshua\nd* went into the temple and started teaching in there.
\v 15 Even the Jewish leaders were surprised, asking, “How can this man know so much when he hasn’t been trained as a teacher?”
\p
\v 16 \nd Yeshua\nd* himself responded, “\wj My teaching doesn’t come from me, but from the one who sent me.\wj*
\v 17 \wj If anyone wants to do God’s will, they’ll soon figure out whether my teaching comes from God or if I’m just making it up myself.\wj*
\v 18 \wj Any person who just teaches their own thoughts is just seeking their own advancement, but anyone who wants to promote the one who sent them, this is authentic and there’s no hidden self-interest.\wj*
\v 19 \wj Didn’t Mosheh write down God’s commandments for you, yet not a single one of you obeys them. Why are you wanting to execute me?\wj*”
\p
\v 20 “You must be demon-possessed,” said some in the crowd, “Who would be wanting to execute you.”
\p
\v 21 \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “\wj I did one miracle and you were all amazed.\wj*
\v 22 \x + \xo 7:22: a \xt Lev 12:3; \xo b \xt Gen 17:10.\x*\wj Mosheh gave you the commandment about circumcision (even though it actually came from before his time), but to obey this, you’ll even circumcise a baby boy on the Rest Day.\wj*
\v 23 \x + \xo 7:23: \xt Yhn 5:9.\x*\wj So if a \add baby\add* boy can be circumcised on the Rest Day so that Mosheh’s commandments aren’t broken, they why did you get angry with me because I made a man healthy on the Rest Day?\wj*
\v 24 \wj Don’t just ‘judge’ things so that you yourselves look good, but judge impartially, seeking the best for others.\wj*”
\s1 Could Yeshua be the messiah?
\p
\v 25 After this, some of the locals from Yerushalem started asking, “Isn’t this the man they were wanting to execute?
\v 26 Well, here he is teaching in public, yet they’re not even confronting him. Perhaps the leaders know that he really is the \nd messiah\nd*?
\v 27 But we even know where this man is from. Surely when the \nd messiah\nd* comes, no one would know his family background.”
\p
\v 28 So as \nd Yeshua\nd* continued teaching, he called out, “\wj Indeed you all know me and my home and my family. But I didn’t come here of my own accord, but the one who sent me here is truthful, even though you don’t even know him.\wj*
\v 29 \wj I know him, because I came from him, indeed, he was the one who sent me here.\wj*”
\p
\v 30 So now they really want to arrest him, but no one touched him because it was not yet the proper time.
\v 31 Many in the crowd did believe that he was from God and they were saying, “When the \nd messiah\nd* comes, would he be doing greater miracles than what we’ve seen this man do?”
\s1 Yeshua discusses leaving as they aim to arrest him
\p
\v 32 The Pharisee party heard the crowd muttering about these things and sent out some of their servants along with the chief priests to go and arrest Yeshua.
\v 33 So \nd Yeshua\nd* said, “\wj I’ll only be with you all for a short while longer and then I’ll be going to the one who sent me.\wj*
\v 34 \wj You’ll look for me but won’t be able to find me, and you can’t go where I’ll be going.\wj*”
\p
\v 35 The leaders wondered, “Where could he be going that we wouldn’t be able to find him? Will he go and live with the Jews living out there among the Greeks and start teaching the Greeks?
\v 36 And what does he mean about looking for him and not being able to find him, and not being able to go where he goes?”
\s1 Yeshua offers living water to the crowd
\p
\v 37 \x + \xo 7:37: \xt Lev 23:36.\x*On the final climax day of the celebrations, \nd Yeshua\nd* stood there and shouted, “\wj Anyone who’s thirsty, come here to me and drink.\wj*
\v 38 \x + \xo 7:38: \xt Eze 47:1; Zech 14:8.\x*\wj Whoever trusts me will have rivers of living water flowing out from him just like the scriptures say.\wj*”
\v 39 He was talking about God’s spirit that the ones who trust him would receive in the future—not yet because \nd Yeshua\nd* hadn’t been lifted up to heaven yet.
\s1 The people are divided about Yeshua
\p
\v 40 When some in the crowd heard his teaching, they said, “He really is the \add coming\add* prophet.”
\v 41 Others said, “He must be the messiah.”
\p But some pointed out, “The messiah won’t come from Galilee.
\v 42 \x + \xo 7:42: \xt 2Sam 7:12; Mic 5:2.\x*Don’t the scriptures say that he’ll be a descendant of King David and that he’ll come from David’s town of Bethlehem?”
\v 43 And so the crowd was divided about Yeshua.
\v 44 Some \add of the Pharisees’ servants\add* wanted to arrest him, but decided to leave him alone \add for now\add*.
\s1 The leaders distrust Yeshua and mock his followers
\p
\v 45 So when the servants returned back to the chief priests and the Pharisees, they were asked, “Why haven’t you brought him?”
\p
\v 46 They answered, “We’ve never heard anyone speak like he does.”
\p
\v 47 “Don’t tell us that you’ve also been taken in by him?” the Pharisees asked them.
\v 48 “None of our leaders or any of us Pharisees believe that he’s from God.
\v 49 But all these people ignorant of the scriptures are bewitched.”
\p
\v 50 \x + \xo 7:50: \xt Yhn 3:1-2.\x*Now Nicodemus (the one who had previously visited Yeshua) spoke up,
\v 51 “Since when did our rules allow us to judge a person before we’ve even heard them out and investigated what they’re doing?”
\p
\v 52 “So do you come from Galilee as well?” they sneered, “Look in the scriptures and you’ll soon see that no prophet emerges out of \em Galilee\em*.”
\rem The story of the woman caught in adultery does not appear in the majority of the oldest manuscripts that we have. Hence, it is not included in this translation.
\rem (That doesn’t necessarily mean that the event never happened—just that it almost certainly wasn’t part of Yohan’s original account.)
\s1 The woman caught in adultery\f + \fr 7:53 \ft This event is not included in the oldest manuscripts that we have. (That doesn’t mean that it’s necessarily fictitious—just that Yohan probably didn’t originally include these events in his account.)\f*
\p
