\v 11 ◘
\s1 The two witnesses of Yeshua’s authenticity
\p
\v 12 \x + \xo 8:12: \xt Mat 5:14; Yhn 9:5.\x*Because of this, \nd Yeshua\nd* told them, “\wj \em I am\em* the light for the world—whoever follows me won’t walk in the darkness but will have the light \add that gives\add* life.\wj*”
\p
\v 13 \x + \xo 8:13: \xt Yhn 5:31.\x*Some from the Pharisee party argued, “You are testifying about yourself, so that testimony is invalid.”
\p
\v 14 \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “\wj Even when I am testifying about myself, my testimony is valid, because I know where I came from and where I’m going.\wj*
\v 15 \wj You all are judging according to your earthly values. I’m not judging anyone.\wj*
\v 16 \wj But even if I was judging, my judgement would be correct, because it wouldn’t just be me judging, but also the father who sent me.\wj*
\v 17 \x + \xo 8:17: \xt Deu 19:15.\x*\wj It’s even written in your own laws that the testimony of two men is valid.\wj*
\v 18 \wj So that’s me testifying about myself, plus the father who sent me also testifies about me.\wj*”
\p
\v 19 “And where is your father?” they asked.
\p \nd Yeshua\nd* answered them, “\wj You don’t know either me or my father. If you did know me, then you’d also know my father.\wj*”
\p
\v 20 He explained all this while he was teaching in the treasury part of the temple, but no one arrested him because the time for his \add suffering\add* had not yet arrived.
\s1 You can’t go where I’m going
\p
\v 21 So he continued, “\wj I will be going away and all of you will be looking for me, but you’ll all just die in your sins and won’t be able to go where I’ll be going.\wj*”
\p
\v 22 This puzzled the Jewish teachers, “Surely he’s not going to commit suicide! What else could he mean about ‘you can’t go where I’m going to be going’?”
\p
\v 23 Yeshua explained, “\wj All of you are from the world below, but I’m from the world above. You all are part of this world, but I’m not part of it.\wj*
\v 24 \wj That’s why I said that you’ll be dying in your sins, because if you refuse to believe that I am \add God\add*, you will indeed all be dying in your sins.\wj*”
\p
\v 25 “So who are you?” they asked.
\p And he answered, “\wj Still just the same as I’ve been telling you from the beginning.\wj*
\v 26 \wj I have a lot that I need to tell you all and to judge many of your actions, because the one who sent me is true, and it’s what I hear from him that I speak to all people.\wj*”
\p
\v 27 (They didn’t realise that he was talking to them about the father \add in heaven\add*.)
\v 28 So \nd Yeshua\nd* told them, “\wj When you all lift up\f + \fr 8:28 \ft lifted up / exalted: There’s a play on words here. See https://bibleDifferences.net/2019/04/25/156-exulted (dead link???)\f* humanity’s child \add on a pole\add*, then you will know that I am \add God\add*, and that I don’t do anything by myself, but I say all this just as the father told me to.\wj*
\v 29 \wj And the one who sent me is with me—he didn’t just leave me alone—because I am continually doing what pleases him.\wj*”
\p
\v 30 After he’d said all this, many people believed in him.
\s1 Yeshua teaches about freedom from slavery
\p
\v 31 Because of this, \nd Yeshua\nd* told all the Jews who believed in him, “\wj If you all continue to believe my message, then you’re my true followers.\wj*
\v 32 \wj You will have known the truth, and the truth will set you free.\wj*”
\p
\v 33 \x + \xo 8:33: \xt Mat 3:9; Luk 3:8.\x*But some queried, “We are Abraham’s descendants and we’ve never been slaves to anyone, so how can you say that we’ll be set free?”
\p
\v 34 “\wj I can assure you all that anyone who sins is a slave to sin,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* answered.
\v 35 “\wj And the slaves don’t necessarily remain in the \add family\add* home forever—only the children have that right.\wj*
\v 36 \wj So if the son sets you free, then you’ll be truly free.\wj*
\s1 Yeshua spars with the Jewish religious leaders
\p
\v 37 “\wj Yes, I know that you’re all descendants of Abraham, but you’re trying to kill me because my message doesn’t lodge in you.\wj*
\v 38 \wj Indeed I talk about what I’ve actually seen with the father, but you all are doing what you’ve heard from your father.\wj*”
\p
\v 39 But they retorted, “Abraham is our father.”\f + \fr 8:39 \ft father meaning ancestor. (Abraham lived some 2,000 years before the time of these events.)\f*
\p And \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “\wj Well, if you really were descendants of Abraham, you’d behave more like him.\wj*
\v 40 \wj But instead you’re trying to find a way to have me killed—to kill the man who has spoken the truth to you—truth that I heard from \nd God\nd*. Abraham never did that.\wj*
\v 41 \wj You’re doing what \em your\em* father wants you all do to.\wj*”
\p But they shot back, “It’s not us who was conceived by a couple that weren’t even married! Anyway, we only have one father and that’s \nd God\nd*.”
\p
\v 42 “\wj If God was your father you all would be loving me,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “\wj because I came from God and for God. I didn’t just come by myself, but God sent me here.\wj*
\v 43 \wj Why can’t you comprehend what I’m saying? The reason that you can’t stand listening to my message\wj*
\v 44 \wj is because you come from your father, the devil, and you want to do what \em your\em* father wants. But he was a murderer from the beginning, and doesn’t stick to the truth because there’s no truth in him. Whenever he tells lies, he’s speaking from his own nature, because he’s a liar and the source of lying.\wj*
\v 45 \wj But because I’m speaking the truth, you don’t believe in me.\wj*
\v 46 \wj Which of you can scold me for my sins? If I am speaking the truth, why don’t you believe I’m from God?\wj*
\v 47 \wj Anyone who belongs to God, listens to what God says. But you all can’t even hear the message, because you don’t belong to God.\wj*”
\s1 Yeshua preceded, and is greater than, Abraham
\p
\v 48 The Jewish leaders asked, “Aren’t we right in saying that you’re from Samaria and that you have a demon?”
\p
\v 49 “\wj No, I don’t have a demon,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj but I honour my father and you’re dishonouring me.\wj*
\v 50 \wj But I’m not searching greatness for myself—my father is the one searching and the one judging.\wj*
\v 51 \wj I can assure you, that anyone who puts my teaching into practice can be certain to avoid death in \add this\add* age.\wj*”
\p
\v 52 “Now we \em know\em* that you have a demon!” the Jews said. “Abraham and the prophets all died, but you’re saying that those who follow your teaching can be certain to avoid death in \add this\add* age.
\v 53 How could you be greater than our ancestor Abraham who died? Even the prophets died. Who do you think you are?”
\p
\v 54 Again \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj If I praise myself, my praise is worthless, but it’s my father who praises me—the one who you say is your \nd God\nd*\wj*
\v 55 \wj although in fact you don’t even know him. But I have known him, and so I can’t say that I haven’t known him or I’d be a liar like all of you. But I have known him and I am putting his desires into practice.\wj*
\v 56 \wj Your ancestor Abraham would have been excited to see me here—in fact he did see ahead and was very happy about it.\wj*”
\p
\v 57 Because of that, the Jewish leaders asked, “You aren’t even fifty years old yet. How could you have seen Abraham?”\f + \fr 8:57 \ft Abraham lived some 2,000 years before Yeshua.\f*
\p
\v 58 \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj I can assure you that \em I am\em*\f + \fr 8:58 \ft This awkward English is necessary to catch the play on words, because ‘I am’ is the meaning of \em Yahweh\em*, the name of God.\f* before Abraham ever existed.\wj*”
\p
\v 59 When they heard that, they picked up rocks to throw at Yeshua \add to kill him\add*. But Yeshua became hidden from their sight, and went on out of the temple.
\c 9
\s1 A blind man obeys and then can see
\p
\v 1 As Yeshua was walking along, he saw a man who had been blind from birth
\v 2 and his followers asked him, “Honoured teacher, why was this man born blind? Was it because he himself sinned, or his parents?”
\p
\v 3 \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj It wasn’t either this man or his parents that sinned.\f + \fr 9:3 \ft We just want to alert our readers here that we have divided the Greek sentences here in a way that’s different from the long-standing tradition. (The Greek originals have no punctuation, so either way is valid.)\f* But so that \nd God\nd* can work in him for others to see,\wj*
\v 4 \wj as long as it’s daytime, we need to do what the one who sent us wants, but when nighttime comes, no one will be able to work.\wj*
\v 5 \x + \xo 9:5: \xt Mat 5:14; Yhn 8:12.\x*\wj As long as I’m here in this world, I am the light of the world.\wj*”
\p
\v 6 After he’d said this, Yeshua spat on the ground and after mixing some clay into a slurry, he spread it on the eyes of the man
\v 7 and told him to go and wash in the Siloam Pool.\f + \fr 9:7 \ft Siloam means ‘to be sent out’.\f*
\p
\v 8 Then the neighbours of the man and others who had seen him earlier, knowing that he was a beggar asked, “Isn’t he the one who always sat and begged here?”
\p
\v 9 And indeed, some were saying, “Yes, this is him.” But others were saying, “No, but he looks quite similar.”
\p And the man said, “I \em am\em* him.”
\p
\v 10 So they asked him, “Well, how come that now you can see?”
\p
\v 11 “A man named \nd Yeshua\nd* made a slurry,” he said, “and spread it on my eyes and told me to go and wash at Siloam Pool. So I went and did it, and when I washed my eyes, I could see.”
\p
\v 12 “Where is he now?” they asked.
\p “I don’t know,” said the man.
\s1 The Pharisees can’t accept the healing of the blind man
\p
\v 13 Then they brought the man who had been blind to the Pharisees.
\v 14 Now, it had been the Rest Day when \nd Yeshua\nd* had made the slurry and enabled him to see,
\v 15 and because of this, some in the Pharisee party asked him how it was that now he could see. And he answered, “Well, he put a slurry on my eyes and when I washed them, I could see.”
\p
\v 16 “Well clearly that man is not from \nd God\nd*,” some of them said, “because he doesn’t respect the Rest Day.”
\p However others said, “But if he’s just a sinner, how could he do miracles like that?”
\p
\v 17 So they asked the man who had been blind, “Well, what do \em you\em* have to say because it was your eyes that he opened?”
\p “He must be a prophet,” the man said.
\p
\v 18 But some of the Jews weren’t even sure that he really had been blind before and could now see, so they called for his parents
\v 19 and asked them, “You two say that this is your son and that he was born blind. If so, how come that now he can see?”
\p
\v 20 His parents answered, “We know that he’s our son, and we know that he was born blind.
\v 21 But as for how come he can now see, we don’t know that. Nor do we know who healed his eyes. But ask him—he’s old enough to speak for himself.”
\v 22 (His parents said these things because they were afraid of the Jewish religious leaders, because the leaders had already announced that anyone who said that Yeshua was the \nd messiah\nd* would get banned from all religious ceremonies,
\v 23 so that’s why they had said, “He’s old enough—just ask him.”)
\p
\v 24 So the leaders summoned the man born blind a second time and commanded him, “Only praise \nd God\nd* himself for this, because we know that that man is a sinner.”
\p
\v 25 “Well, I don’t know whether or not he’s a sinner,” replied the man. “All I know is that I used to be blind but now I can see.”
\p
\v 26 “What did he do to you?” they asked again. “How did he open your eyes?”
\p
\v 27 And he answered, “I already told you that, and you didn’t even listen. Why do you want to hear it all over again? Do you guys all want to become his followers as well?”
\p
\v 28 Then they insulted him and said, “\em You\em* might be a follower of that man, but \em we\em* are followers of Mosheh.
\v 29 We know that \nd God\nd* spoke to Mosheh, but we don’t even know where this other fellow is from.”
\p
\v 30 “Wow, that’s pretty amazing,” the man responded. “That man opened up my eyes, and you teachers don’t even know where he’s from!
\v 31 We know that \nd God\nd* doesn’t listen to sinners, but he listens to those who worship him and do what he wants.
\v 32 In all the centuries past we never heard that a person could give sight to someone who was born blind.
\v 33 If this man isn’t from \nd God\nd*, surely he wouldn’t be able to do that!”
\p
\v 34 They reacted, “You’re just an ignorant sinner, and you think you can teach \em us\em*!” Then they had him thrown out of the room.
\s1 Spiritual blindness and hypocrisy
\p
\v 35 \nd Yeshua\nd* heard that they had thrown out the man who could now see, and when he found him, he said, “\wj Do you believe that humanity’s child \add came from God\add*?\wj*”
\p
\v 36 And the man answered, “Mister, who is he so that I can believe in him?”
\p
\v 37 “\wj You’ve seen him and heard him and he’s speaking to you right now,\wj*” said \nd Yeshua\nd*.
\p
\v 38 “I do believe, \nd master\nd*,” the man responded. Then he knelt down in front of Yeshua.
\p
\v 39 \nd Yeshua\nd* said, “\wj I came into this world to dispense judgement, so that the people who can’t see will be able to see, and so that the ones who can see will become blind.\wj*”
\p
\v 40 The Pharisees with him heard that and asked, “Are you saying that we’re blind?”
\p
\v 41 “\wj If you were blind,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* replied, “\wj you wouldn’t be sinning, but since you all declare that you can see, then your sin remains.\wj*
\c 10
\s1 The sheep know their true master
\p
\v 1 “\wj Honestly I can tell you: It’s not the person that enters the sheep enclosure by the gate that is a thief and robber, but rather the one who climbs in a different way.\wj*
\v 2 \wj The one that comes in the gate is the shepherd of the sheep.\wj*
\v 3 \wj The gatekeeper opens up for him, and when he calls the sheep by name they listen to his voice and he leads them out.\wj*
\v 4 \wj Whenever he moves the sheep, he goes in front and the sheep follow him because they recognise his voice.\wj*
\v 5 \wj They would never follow a stranger because they wouldn’t know his voice, in fact they’d run away from him.\wj*”
\p
\v 6 \nd Yeshua\nd* told them this illustration, but none of those who heard it knew what it meant.
\s1 Yeshua is the good shepherd
\p
\v 7 So \nd Yeshua\nd* continued, “\wj Honestly I will tell you that \em I am\em* the entrance for the sheep.\wj*
\v 8 \wj The ones who came before me are thieves and robbers, but the sheep didn’t listen to them.\wj*
\v 9 \wj \em I am\em* the entrance. Anyone who comes in via me will be saved, and will be able to go in and out and find pasture.\wj*
\v 10 \wj The thief only comes to steal and kill and destroy, but I came so that they could live, and live a full life.\wj*
\p
\v 11 “\wj \em I am\em* the good shepherd—the good shepherd gives his own life for the sheep.\wj*\f + \fr 10:11 \ft See http://bibleandtech.blogspot.com/2021/04/john-1011-18-translations-and-notes-rcl.html\f*
\v 12 \wj The paid worker is not even the shepherd, because the sheep aren’t his own and if he sees a wolf coming he just abandons the sheep and takes off and the wolf scatters the sheep and snatches some—\wj*
\v 13 \wj that’s because he’s just a worker and doesn’t really care about the sheep.\wj*
\v 14 \wj \em I am\em* the good shepherd and I know my \add sheep\add* and they know me,\wj*
\v 15 \x + \xo 10:15: \xt Mat 11:27; Luk 10:22.\x*\wj just like the father knows me and I know the father—in fact I will give my life for the sheep.\wj*
\v 16 \wj I also have other sheep which are not in this field and it’s appropriate for me to bring those other sheep also, then they’ll be hearing my voice because there’ll be just one flock with one shepherd.\wj*
\p
\v 17 \wj The father loves me because I am laying down my life so that I can take it back again.\wj*
\v 18 \wj No one is taking it from me, but I’m laying it down myself. I have authority to lay it down, and also authority to take it back again because I received this command from my father.\wj*”
\p
\v 19 The Jewish religious leaders were again divided about Yeshua’s teaching
\v 20 with many of them saying, “He’s got a demon,” and, “He’s stark raving mad—why are you all even listening to him!”
\p
\v 21 But others were saying, “He doesn’t sound like he’s demon-possessed. And how could a demon make a blind man see?”
\s1 The Jewish leaders won’t accept Yeshua’s teaching
\p
\v 22 By then it was winter and the time for the Jewish Festival of Dedication in Yerushalem.
\v 23 \nd Yeshua\nd* was walking in the temple in an area known as Solomon’s Porch
\v 24 when he was surrounded by the Jewish religious leaders and interrogated, “How long do you plan to keep us in suspense for? If you are the \nd messiah\nd*, just tell us clearly.”
\p
\v 25 “\wj I already told you all,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj but you didn’t believe me. The miracles that I do with the authority of my father testify about me,\wj*
\v 26 \wj but you don’t accept what the miracles point to because you aren’t part of my flock.\wj*
\v 27 \wj My sheep listen to my voice, and I know them and they follow after me.\wj*
\v 28 \wj I give them life which will never end so they won’t ever be destroyed, and no one will be able to snatch them away from me.\wj*
\v 29 \wj My father is the one who gave them to me, and he’s more powerful than any other, so no one can snatch them away from him.\wj*
\v 30 \wj The father and I are one.\wj*”
\p
\v 31 Again the Jewish leaders picked up rocks to throw at him to kill him
\v 32 but \nd Yeshua\nd* asked them, “\wj I showed you all many miracles from my father. Which miracle do you want to kill me for?\wj*”
\p
\v 33 \x + \xo 10:33: \xt Lev 24:16.\x*They answered, “It’s not for any \em good\em* deed that we think you deserve to die, but because you, a human, dishonour \nd God\nd* by claiming to be him.”
\p
\v 34 \x + \xo 10:34: \xt Psa 82:6.\x*\nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj Isn’t it written in your scriptures that God said, ‘You all are gods’?\wj*
\v 35 \wj Now the scriptures can’t be wrong, and if the ones who heard teaching from \nd God\nd* were called gods,\wj*
\v 36 \wj why are you telling the one that the father blessed and sent out into the world that I am insulting God because I said that I’m God’s son?\wj*
\v 37 \wj If I’m not doing my father’s work, then you don’t need to believe that he sent me,\wj*
\v 38 \wj but if I am doing his work, even if you don’t believe that he sent me, at least believe in what I do so that you all can know that the father is in me and I’m in the father.\wj*”
\p
\v 39 That was enough that they tried yet again to arrest him, but he was able to get out and away from their influence.
\p
\v 40 \x + \xo 10:40: \xt Yhn 1:28.\x*Then Yeshua crossed the Yordan river to the place where Yohan had immersed the people, and he stayed there.
\v 41 Many people visited him there, and they were saying that even though Yohan had never done even one miracle, on the other hand everything that he had said about Yeshua was true,
\v 42 and many people there believed that Yeshua was from God.
\c 11
\s1 Yeshua is aware of Lazarus’ death from afar
\p
\v 1 \x + \xo 11:1: \xt Luk 10:38-39.\x*Now there was a man called Lazarus who lived in the village of Bethany along with his sisters Martha and Maria.
\v 2 \x + \xo 11:2: \xt Yhn 12:3.\x*(Maria was the one who \jmp later|link-href="#C12V3"\jmp* poured fragrant oil over Yeshua and wiped his feet with her hair.) But now their brother was seriously ill
\v 3 and so the two sisters sent a message to Yeshua saying, “\nd Master\nd*, this man that you love is seriously ill.”
\p
\v 4 However, when \nd Yeshua\nd* got the message he said \add to those around him\add*, “\wj This sickness won’t end in death but in honour for \nd God\nd*, so that his son will also be honoured because of it.\wj*”
\p
\v 5 Now it was true that \nd Yeshua\nd* loved the three of them.
\v 6 Yet when he heard that Lazarus was sick, he stayed in the place where he was for two more days
\v 7 before he said to his followers, “\wj It’s time to head down to Yudea again.\wj*”
\p
\v 8 But they double-checked, “Honoured teacher, the Yudeans wanted to execute you, so do you really want to go back there again?”
\p
\v 9 And \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj There are twelve hours of light in the day. Anyone who walks during the daytime doesn’t stumble because he is seeing the light \add that shines in\add* this world.\wj*
\v 10 \wj But anyone who walks at night will stumble, because the light is not in them.\wj*”
\v 11 And he continued, “\wj Our friend Lazarus has fallen asleep, but I’m going so that I can wake him up.\wj*”
\p
\v 12 But his followers objected, “\nd Master\nd*, \add it’s good\add* if he’s sleeping because it helps with healing.”
\p
\v 13 But \nd Yeshua\nd* had spoken about Lazarus’ death—not just normal sleep as they had thought.
\v 14 So \nd Yeshua\nd* told them plainly, “\wj Lazarus is dead\wj*
\v 15 \wj and I’m glad that I wasn’t there, because you all will benefit as your faith grows. Anyway, let’s get moving.\wj*”
\p
\v 16 Thomas (nicknamed ‘Twin’) grumbled to the others, “Yeah, we might as well go so that we can get killed as well.”
\s1 Yeshua is the resurrection and the life
\p
\v 17 So when they eventually arrived, \nd Lazarus\nd* body had already been in the burial chamber for four days.
\v 18 The village of Bethany was less than three kilometres from Yerushalem,
\v 19 so many of the Yudeans from there had come out to console Martha and Maria after the death of their brother.
\p
\v 20 As soon as Martha heard that \nd Yeshua\nd* had arrived, she went out to meet him, but Maria stayed behind where she was sitting in the house.
\v 21 Martha cried, “\nd Yeshua\nd*, \nd master\nd*. If you’d been here, my brother wouldn’t have died,
\v 22 because I already know that anything that you ask from \nd God\nd*, he will give it to you.”
\p
\v 23 \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “\wj Your brother will come back to life.\wj*”
\p
\v 24 “Yes, I know that he’ll come back to life at the resurrection on the last day,” said Martha.
\p
\v 25 But \nd Yeshua\nd* continued, “\wj \em I am\em* the resurrection and the life. Anyone who believes that I’m from God, even if they die they’ll still be living,\wj*
\v 26 \wj and everyone who’s alive and believes that I was sent from God, will not die in the \add next\add* age.\wj*”
\p
\v 27 Martha replied, “Yes, \nd master\nd*, I do believe that you’re the \nd messiah\nd*, God’s son, the one sent into this world.”
\s1 Yeshua weeps with his close friends
\p
\v 28 After saying this, Martha went and quietly called her sister Maria, “The teacher is on his way and he wants to see you.”
\v 29 So Maria quickly got up and went to find him.
\v 30 At that stage, \nd Yeshua\nd* hadn’t yet come into the village proper, but was still at the edge where Martha had met him.
\v 31 The Yudean people who’d been sitting with Maria in sympathy there in the house, when they saw her get up quickly and go out, they assumed that she was going to the cemetery to weep there.
\p
\v 32 But when Maria found \nd Yeshua\nd*, she knelt at his feet and said, “\nd Master\nd*, if you’d been here my brother wouldn’t have died.”
\p
\v 33 Now when \nd Yeshua\nd* saw her weeping there, along with the others that had followed also weeping, he himself was quite affected and groaned inside,
\v 34 but he just asked, “\wj Where has he been laid?\wj*”
\p “\nd Master\nd*, come and see,” they replied.
\p
\v 35 Then \nd Yeshua\nd* \add broke down and\add* burst into tears,
\v 36 which made the others comment, “See how much he cared about him.”
\p
\v 37 But some of them mocked, “This is the man who could make a blind man see again, yet how come he wasn’t able to stop this man from dying!”
\s1 Yeshua calls Lazarus back to life
\p
\v 38 So \nd Yeshua\nd* who was still holding back sobs, went to the cemetery. Lazarus’ body had been placed in a cave with a stone blocking it,
\v 39 and \nd Yeshua\nd* instructed them to take away the stone.
\p Martha (the sister of the dead man) spoke up, “\nd Master\nd*, the stink will be bad because it’s already been four days.”
\p
\v 40 But \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “\wj Didn’t I tell you that if you would believe, then you would see God’s power?\wj*”
\v 41 So they took the stone away and \nd Yeshua\nd* looked upwards and said, “Father, I thank you that you listen to me.
\v 42 Actually I know that you always hear me, but I said that for the sake of these people so that they will believe that it was you who sent me here.”
\v 43 After saying that, he shouted, “\wj Lazarus, come out!\wj*”
\v 44 Then the man who had died \add slowly\add* shuffled out—still with linen strips wrapped around his hands and his feet, and a cloth wrapped around his face.
\s1 The leaders create a plan to execute Yeshua
\r (Mat. 26:1-5; Mark 14:1-2; Luke 22:1-2)
\p
\v 45 Because of that, many of the Yudeans believed that Yeshua was from God after having followed Maria and seeing what Yeshua did.
\v 46 But others went and told the Pharisee party what \nd Yeshua\nd* had done.
\v 47 So the chief priests and the Pharisee party called a formal meeting and asked, “What should we do because this man is doing many miracles.
\v 48 If we allow him to continue like this, all the crowds will be believing he’s the messiah, and then the Romans will come and destroy both our temple and our governance.”
\p
\v 49 But one of them, Caiaphas who was chief priest that year, spoke up, “You don’t know anything.
\v 50 Don’t you all realise that its better for all of us if one man dies so that the people and the nation won’t be destroyed?”
\v 51 (He didn’t say this from his own thinking, but being chief priest that year, he was announcing God’s message that \nd Yeshua\nd* was going to die for the nation,
\v 52 and not only for this nation, but for all of God’s children scattered around the world to become united.)
\p
\v 53 As a result, from that day on they decided that Yeshua needed to be executed.
\v 54 Because of that, \nd Yeshua\nd* no longer walked around Yudea in public, but went out to the town of Ephraim out in the wilderness and stayed there with his followers.
\p
\v 55 At that time, the Jewish Passover celebrations were approaching, and many people from the regions went to Yerushalem ahead of the celebrations to purify themselves.
\v 56 They were looking out for \nd Yeshua\nd* and as they stood around in the temple, they asked each other, “What do you think? Surely he won’t come to the celebrations.”
\v 57 The chief priests and the Pharisee party had already announced that if anyone knew where Yeshua was, they must inform them so that they could arrest him.
\c 12
\s1 Maria sacrifices expensive fragrant oil
\r (Mat. 26:6-13; Mark 14:3-9)
\p
\v 1 Because of this, \nd Yeshua\nd* went to Bethany six days before the Passover. This was where Lazarus lived, the one he had brought back to life.
\v 2 So they prepared dinner for him there and Martha was serving and Lazarus was among those sitting with Yeshua.
\v 3 \x + \xo 12:3: \xt Luk 7:37-38.\x*Then Maria took about 300g of very expensive nard oil and smeared it on \nd Yeshua’s\nd* feet, and then wiped off his feet with her own hair, and the house was filled with the fragrance of the oil.
\v 4 But Yudas, one of Yeshua’s apprentices (the one who would eventually turn him in) complained,
\v 5 “How come this lotion wasn’t sold for almost a year’s wages and then the money given to the poor?”
\v 6 But he didn’t say this because he cared for poor people, but because he carried the purse for the group and used to steal from it.
\p
\v 7 But \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “\wj Let her continue. She has kept this for the time of my burial.\wj*
\v 8 \x + \xo 12:8: \xt Deu 15:11.\x*\wj You’ll always have poor people with you, but you won’t always have me here.\wj*”
\s1 The leaders also plan to kill Lazarus
\p
\v 9 When it was discovered that Yeshua was there \add in Bethany\add*, many Yudeans started arriving, not only because of Yeshua, but also to see Lazarus who’d been dead and Yeshua had brought him back to life.
\v 10 But the chief priests decided in a meeting that they should also have Lazarus killed,
\v 11 because many people were ignoring them and instead were believing that \nd Yeshua\nd* \add came from God\add*.
\s1 Yeshua rides into Yerushalem with many cheers
\r (Mat. 21:1-11; Mark 11:1-11; Luke 19:28-40)
\p
\v 12 The next day a large crowd of people who had come for the celebrations and had heard that \nd Yeshua\nd* was coming to Yerushalem
\v 13 \x + \xo 12:13: \xt Psa 118:25-26.\x*took \add long\add* branches from palm trees and brought them out as they went to meet him. They called out, “Honoured saviour! The one coming in the authority of the \nd master\nd* has been blessed \add by God\add*. This is Israel’s king.”
\p
\v 14 Now \nd Yeshua\nd* had found a young donkey and rode it \add into the city\add* just like it was written in the scriptures,
\q1
\v 15 \x + \xo 12:15: \xt Zech 9:9.\x*“Don’t be worried you children of Tsiyyon/Zion. Your king is coming mounted on a donkey’s foal.”
\p
\v 16 (\nd Yeshua’s\nd* apprentices didn’t realise all these things at the time, but it was later after Yeshua was lifted up to heaven that they were reminded that these things had been written about him, and that they had \add indeed\add* happened to him.)
\p
\v 17 People in the crowd were telling each other about how they’d been with Yeshua when he’d called Lazarus out from the burial chamber and brought him back to life,
\v 18 So because of this, others also wanted to met Yeshua because they’d heard that he’d done that miracle.
\v 19 So the Pharisees discussed this together, “We’re getting nowhere with this. Look, it seems like the whole world wants to follow him.”
\s1 Some Greeks want to meet Yeshua
\p
\v 20 And some Greek people were also going to Yerushalem to worship God at the celebrations
\v 21 and they approached Philip from Bethsaida (up in Galilee) and asked him, “Mister, we’d like to meet this \nd Yeshua\nd*.”
\v 22 So Philip went and told Andrew, and the two of them went and told \nd Yeshua\nd*.
\s1 Yeshua predicts his death again
\p
\v 23 Now \nd Yeshua\nd* told them, “\wj The time has come for humanity’s child to be honoured.\wj*
\v 24 \wj I can assure you that unless a wheat seed drops into the ground and dies, it will stay just as it is, but if it dies, it’s able to produce a harvest.\wj*
\v 25 \x + \xo 12:25: \xt Mat 10:39; 16:25; Mrk 8:35; Luk 9:24; 17:33.\x*\wj Anyone who loves their life will lose it, but the person hating their life in this world will stay alive forever.\wj*
\v 26 \wj Anyone who wants to serve me needs to follow after me, so that wherever I am, my servant will also be there. Anyone who serves me will be honoured by the father.\wj*
\p
\v 27 \wj Now, I’m very troubled. What else could I say other than, ‘Father, let me avoid what’s coming.’ But it was exactly this that I came for.\wj*
\v 28 \wj Father, may your authority and be honoured.\wj*”
\p And a voice from the sky answered, “I’ve already brought honour to it and will do so again.”
\p
\v 29 This caused some in the crowd standing there to say that they’d heard thunder while others said that a messenger must have spoken to Yeshua.
\p
\v 30 “\wj That voice wasn’t for my sake,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “\wj but for all of you.\wj*
\v 31 \wj This world is about to be judged and its ruler will be thrown out,\wj*
\v 32 \wj and when I’m lifted up\f + \fr 12:32 \ft lifted up / exalted: See https://bibleDifferences.net/2019/04/25/156-exulted\f* from the earth, I will attract everyone towards me.\wj*”
\v 33 By saying this, he was indicating how he was going to die.
\p
\v 34 \x + \xo 12:34: \xt Psa 110:4; Isa 9:7; Eze 37:25; Dan 7:14.\x*So the crowd queried him, “We heard from the scriptures that the \nd messiah\nd* will stay until the end of the age so why do you say that humanity’s child will be lifted up. And who is this ‘humanity’s child’?”
\p
\v 35 \nd Yeshua\nd* answered them, “\wj The light will be among you all for just a little bit longer, so get walking while you have the light so that you won’t have to deal with darkness. Anyone walking in the dark doesn’t know where they’re going.\wj*
\v 36 \wj While you still have the light, believe in the light so that you will become children of light.\wj*”
\p \nd Yeshua\nd* said these things and then after leaving them, he was hidden from them.
\s1 Many people refuse to stand for Yeshua
\p
\v 37 Even though Yeshua had done so many miracles in front of the people, they didn’t believe that he was the messiah.
\v 38 \x + \xo 12:38: \xt Isa 53:1 (LXX).\x*This fulfilled what the prophet Isayah wrote,
\q1 “\nd Master\nd*, who believed our report?
\q1 And who was the master’s power revealed to?”
\p
\v 39 Because of this, they weren’t able to believe, and again as Isayah wrote,
\q1
\v 40 \x + \xo 12:40: \xt Isa 6:10 (LXX).\x*“He has blinded their eyes and maimed their emotions,
\q1 so that they can’t see with their eyes and understand with their minds,
\q2 or they might be turned and then I would heal them.”
\p
\v 41 Isayah wrote this because he saw the messiah’s greatness and spoke concerning him.
\v 42 Likewise, many of the Jewish leaders believed that Yeshua was the messiah, but they didn’t tell others because they didn’t want the Pharisee party to banish them from their services
\v 43 as they valued the praise of people more than praise from \nd God\nd*.
\s1 It’s Yeshua’s teachings that will judge the hearers
\p
\v 44 Then \nd Yeshua\nd* called out, “\wj Anyone who believes that I came from God is not \add just\add* believing in me, but \add also\add* believing in the one who sent me,\wj*
\v 45 \wj and anyone who watches me \add working\add*, is watching the one who sent me.\wj*
\v 46 \wj I came into this world as light so that anyone who believes in me won’t have darkness residing in them.\wj*
\v 47 \wj I won’t be judging anyone who hears my teaching and doesn’t obey it, because I didn’t come to judge the world but rather to save it.\wj*
\v 48 \wj Anyone who rejects me and doesn’t accept my teaching does have a judge though—it’s the message that I spoke that will judge them at the end of time\wj*
\v 49 \wj because I wasn’t speaking from my own thoughts, but it was the father himself who sent me that told me what to say and what to teach.\wj*
\v 50 \wj And I’m fully aware that \add obeying\add* his commands leads to living forever. Therefore whenever I speak, I just say whatever the father said to me.\wj*”
\c 13
\s1 Yeshua washes the feet of his apprentices
\p
\v 1 Even before the actual feast part of the Passover celebrations, \nd Yeshua\nd* knew that his time had come—the time when he would leave this world and \add return\add* to the father. He loved his followers who were in the world right through to the end.
\p
\v 2 And now it was getting near time for the dinner and the devil had already put into Yudas Iscariot’s mind \add the idea\add* of handing Yeshua over \add to the authorities\add*.
\v 3 Yeshua knew that the father had given everything to him, putting it under his control, and he knew that he had come from God and would return to God.
\v 4 So he got up from the dinner \add table\add*, changed out of his clothes, and wrapped a linen towel around himself.
\v 5 Then he put water into the wash bowl and started washing the feet of his apprentices, wiping them dry with the linen towel that was he was wearing wrapped around him.
\v 6 After he’d washed a few, he got to Simon Peter who asked him, “\nd Master\nd*, are you going to wash my feet?”
\p
\v 7 “\wj What I’m doing now,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj you won’t really understand, but in the future you will.\wj*”
\p
\v 8 Peter responded, “Well I’m never ever going to let you wash \em my\em* feet!”
\p “\wj If I don’t wash them,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj then you won’t be included in my \add group\add*.\wj*”
\p
\v 9 “Well, if that’s so,” Peter said, “don’t just wash my feet but my hands and my head as well.”
\p
\v 10 \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “\wj Any person who’s already washed \add themselves\add* only needs to wash their feet now to be clean. And so you’re clean, but not every one of you.\wj*”
\v 11 He said this last bit because he already knew who was going to hand him over.
\p
\v 12 \x + \xo 13:12-15: \xt Luk 22:27.\x*So when he’d finished washing their feet, he got dressed again and sat down and asked, “\wj Do you know what I just did to you all?\wj*
\v 13 \wj You call me teacher and \nd master\nd*, and so you should, because I am.\wj*
\v 14 \wj So if the \nd master\nd* and teacher of you all washed your feet, then you also ought to wash each other’s feet.\wj*
\v 15 \wj I have given this to you all as an example that you can also do to others.\wj*
\v 16 \x + \xo 13:16: \xt Mat 10:24; Luk 6:40; Yhn 15:20.\x*\wj I can assure you that a slave isn’t greater than his master, and an missionary isn’t greater than the \add king\add* who sends him.\wj*
\v 17 \wj If you can figure all this out and then do it, you will be blessed \add by God\add*.\wj*
\p
\v 18 \x + \xo 13:18: \xt Psa 41:9.\x*“\wj But I’m not talking about all of you. I know each one that I chose, but this that was \add written\add* in the scriptures must be fulfilled,\wj*
\q1 \wj ‘The one sharing food with me, lifted up his boot against me.’\wj*
\m
\v 19 \wj So I’m telling you now before it happens so that when it does happen, then you’ll all believe that I am \add the messiah\add*.\wj*
\v 20 \x + \xo 13:20: \xt Mat 10:40; Mrk 9:37; Luk 9:48; 10:16.\x*\wj I can assure you all that anyone who accepts any person that I might send, they’re accepting me, and anyone who accepts me, is accepting the one who sent me.\wj*”
\s1 Yeshua indicates who will hand him over
\r (Mat. 26:20-25; Mark 14:17-21; Luke 22:21-23)
\p
\v 21 After saying these things, \nd Yeshua\nd* thoughts were troubled and he said, “\wj I can assure you that one of you will be turning me in.\wj*”
\p
\v 22 This made his apprentices glance around at each other, puzzled about which one he was talking about.
\v 23 \nd One\nd* of them that \nd Yeshua\nd* especially liked,\f + \fr 13:23 \ft This apprentice, unnamed here, is assumed to be the author of this account (being shy or modest).\f* was leaning against him \add at the table\add*.
\v 24 So Simon Peter nodded to him to find out who Yeshua had been talking about,
\v 25 and he leaned back on \nd Yeshua\nd* and asked \add quietly\add*, “\nd Master\nd*, who is it?”
\p
\v 26 “\wj It’s the one I hand this piece of bread to after I’ve dipped it \add in the sauce\add*,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* answered. Then after dipping his piece of bread in, he gave it to Yudas Iscariot.
\v 27 After accepting the piece of bread, Satan entered into Yudas, and then \nd Yeshua\nd* told him, “What you’re about to do, do it soon.”
\v 28 But none of the others sitting around the table knew what Yeshua meant.
\v 29 Some of them thought that since Yudas held their purse, perhaps \nd Yeshua\nd* was getting him to buy something they needed for the feast or to give something to the poor.
\p
\v 30 Anyway, having eaten the piece of bread, Yudas went straight outside where it was already dark.
\s1 The new command to love each other
\p
\v 31 After Yudas had gone, \nd Yeshua\nd* told the others, “\wj Now humanity’s child will be honoured and \nd God\nd* will be honoured through him.\wj*
\v 32 \wj Also \nd God\nd* himself will be honouring him and will do that immediately.\wj*
\v 33 \wj My friends, I’ll only be with you a little bit longer. Then you’ll all look for me and as I told\x + \xo 13:33: \xt Yhn 7:34.\x* the religious leaders, you won’t be able to go where I’m going. So now I’ve also told all of you.\wj*
\v 34 \x + \xo 13:34: \xt Yhn 15:12,17; 1Yhn 3:23; 2Yhn 5.\x*\wj I’m giving you a new commandment—you need to love each other. The way that I loved all of you is how you should love each other.\wj*
\v 35 \wj This is actually how you’ll know if you are my followers: if you are loving each other.\wj*”
\s1 Yeshua predicts that Peter will disown him
\r (Mat. 26:31-35; Mark 14:27-31; Luke 22:31-34)
\p
\v 36 Now Peter followed-up, “\nd Master\nd*, where are you going?”
\p “\wj Where I’m going,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj you won’t be able to follow me at this stage, but you will follow me eventually.\wj*”
\p
\v 37 Peter asked again, “Why can’t I follow after you now? I’m prepared to give my life for you.”
\p
\v 38 “\wj You think you’ll be giving your life for me?\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* responded. “\wj I can assure you that the rooster won’t crow until you’ve already disowned knowing me three times.\wj*”
\c 14
\s1 Yeshua is the road to the father but will be leaving
\p
\v 1 \add Yeshua continued telling them,\add* “\wj Don’t be living in fear. You believe that \nd God\nd* is real, and you also believe that I was sent by him.\wj*
\v 2 \wj There are many places to live in my father’s residence—I would have told you if there wasn’t because I’m going there to prepare a place for all of you.\wj*
\v 3 \wj And after I’ve gone to prepare that place, then I’ll be coming back again and will bring you to myself, so that where I am, you can all be there also.\wj*
\v 4 \wj You know how to get where I’m going.\wj*”
\p
\v 5 “\nd Master\nd*,” Thomas asked, “we don’t \add even\add* know \em where\em* you’re going, let alone how to get there.”
\p
\v 6 And \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj \em I am\em* the path and the truth and the life. No one can get to the father except via me.\wj*
\v 7 \wj If you had all known me, you would also have known my father, and from now on you do know him and have seen him.\wj*”
\p
\v 8 So Philip said, “\nd Master\nd*, show us the father and that’ll be enough for us.”
\p
\v 9 “\wj I’ve been with you all for quite some time,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* replied, “\wj and yet you still don’t \add even\add* know me, Philip.\wj*
\v 10 \wj You don’t believe that I am in the father and the father is in me. These things that I’ve been telling you all, I don’t \add just\add* make them up myself, but the father who lives in me is doing what he wants.\wj*
\v 11 \wj You all need to believe that I am in the father and the father is in me. If that’s hard, at least believe it because of what he’s doing.\wj*
\v 12 \wj I can assure you all that anyone who believes \add that God sent\add* me and is the source of the miracles that I do, that person will be able to do the same and even greater miracles because I am going to the father.\wj*
\v 13 \wj Whatever you request from me with my name and authority, I will do it so that the father might be honoured because of the son.\wj*
\v 14 \wj Anything that you all request using my name and authority will be done.\wj*
\s1 The father will be sending a different advocate
\p
\v 15 “\wj If you all love me, you will obey my commands.\wj*
\v 16 \wj And I will ask the father and he will give you another assistant to be with you all for this age—\wj*
\v 17 \wj the \nd spirit\nd* of truth. The world cannot accept him, because it doesn’t see or know him.\wj*
\p
\v 18 “\wj And I won’t leave you all here as orphans, but I will come back to you.\wj*
\v 19 \wj It won’t be long now and the world won’t see me any more, but you will see me because I’ll be alive and you all will be alive also.\wj*
\v 20 \wj At that time you will know that I am in my father, and you all are in me, and I am in you all.\wj*
\p
\v 21 “\wj Anyone who takes my commands and obeys them, that’s the person who loves me, and anyone who loves me will be loved by my father, and I \add too\add* will be loving them and will be revealing myself to them.\wj*”
\p
\v 22 Yudas (not Yudas Iscariot) asked, “\nd Master\nd*, what’s going on? Why would you reveal yourself to us and not to the \add whole\add* world?”
\p
\v 23 \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj If anyone loves me, they’ll obey my teaching, and my father will love them and we will go to that person and live with them.\wj*
\v 24 \wj But anyone who doesn’t love me, won’t obey my teaching. The words that you hear from me are not my own, but come from the father who sent me.\wj*
\p
\v 25 “\wj I told you all this while I have been here with you all.\wj*
\v 26 \wj But the holy \nd spirit\nd*, the assistant who the father will be sending with my authority, he will be teaching you everything, and will be reminding you of everything that I told you all.\wj*
\p
\v 27 \wj I will leave peace with you all. I’m giving my peace to you all, but what I’m giving isn’t like what the world gives. Don’t be upset or afraid.\wj*
\v 28 \wj You all heard me say that I’m going away and then will be coming back. If you really loved me, you’d be very happy that I’m going to the father, because the father is greater than me.\wj*
\p
\v 29 \wj But I’ve told you now before it happens, so that when it does come to pass, you’ll be able to believe \add that it was preplanned\add*.\wj*
\v 30 \wj I won’t have much more time to talk to you, because the ruler of the world is coming and he has nothing in common with me,\wj*
\v 31 \wj but he’s coming so that the world can know that I love the father and whatever the father told me to do, I’m doing it.\wj*
\p “\wj Come on, stand up. We need to be leaving this place.\wj*”
\c 15
\s1 The branches must stay connected to the vine
\p
\v 1 “\wj \em I am\em* the true vine and my father is the farmer.\wj*
\v 2 \wj He removes every one of my branches that doesn’t bear fruit, but those that do bear fruit, he prunes them so they’ll produce even more.\wj*
\v 3 \wj You are all clean already because of the teaching that I’ve given you.\wj*
\v 4 \wj Stay in me, and I will stay in you all, because just as a branch can’t bear fruit in isolation when it’s not connected to the vine, neither can you if you don’t stay in me.\wj*
\p
\v 5 “\wj \em I am\em* the vine and you all are the branches. Anyone who stays in me will produce a lot of fruit—apart from me you can’t do anything.\wj*
\v 6 \wj Anyone who doesn’t stay in me will be thrown away like a branch, and will wither and be gathered together with others, and thrown into the fire to be burnt.\wj*
\v 7 \wj If you stay in me and my teaching stays in you, then you can request whatever you all want and it will be done for you.\wj*
\v 8 \wj My father will be honoured and praised when you produce a lot of fruit, and you all become my followers.\wj*
\v 9 \wj I loved you all just as the father loved me, so stay in my love.\wj*
\v 10 \wj If you obey my commands, you all will be staying in my love, just like I’ve obeyed my father’s commands and I am staying in his love.\wj*
\p
\v 11 “\wj I’ve told you these things so that I’ll be happy with you all, and so that your happiness will be genuine and long-lasting.\wj*
\v 12 \x + \xo 15:12: \xt Yhn 13:34; 15:17; 1Yhn 3:23; 2Yhn 5.\x*\wj So here’s my request: keep loving each other just like I loved you all.\wj*
\v 13 \wj No one has greater love than the one who gives up their own life for their friends.\wj*
\v 14 \wj You are my friends if you do what I am telling you.\wj*
\v 15 \wj I’m not calling you slaves, because a slave doesn’t know his master’s plans, but I’m calling you friends because I’ve told you everything that I heard from my father.\wj*
\v 16 \wj You didn’t choose me, but I chose you all, and I assigned you to go and produce fruit and for your fruit to be permanent so that whatever you request from the father in my name and authority, he will give it to you.\wj*
\v 17 \wj I am telling you all this so that you can all love each other.\wj*
\s1 People will hate Yeshua-followers
\p
\v 18 “\wj If the world hates you, you all know that it hated me before it hated you.\wj*
\v 19 \wj If you belonged to this world, then the world would love you as it loves its own people, but you don’t belong to this world because I chose you out of it. That’s why they hate all of you.\wj*
\v 20 \x + \xo 15:20: \xt Mat 10:24; Luk 6:40; Yhn 13:16.\x*\wj Remember that I told you that slaves are not greater than their master. So if they persecuted me, they’ll also be persecuting you all. (If they’d obeyed my teaching, they would also obey your teaching.)\wj*
\v 21 \wj But they will do all these things against you because of my name, because they don’t know the father who sent me.\wj*
\v 22 \wj They wouldn’t be considered sinners except that I came and spoke to them, so now they don’t have any excuse for their sin.\wj*
\v 23 \wj Anyone who hates me, also hates my father.\wj*
\v 24 \wj If I hadn’t done miracles among them of the sort that no one else has done, they wouldn’t be considered to be sinners, but now they’ve observed me and hated both me and my father.\wj*
\v 25 \x + \xo 15:25: \xt Psa 35:19; 69:4.\x*\wj The writings of the prophets will certainly come to pass, that ‘they hated me undeservedly’.\wj*
\p
\v 26 “\wj When the assistant arrives that I will send to you all from the father, the \nd spirit\nd* of truth coming from the father, he will tell the truth about me.\wj*
\v 27 \wj You also will be able to tell the truth about me because you all were with me from the beginning.\wj*
\c 16
\p
\v 1 “\wj I’ve told you this so that you won’t stumble.\wj*
\v 2 \wj First they will ban you all from their religious services, then there’s a time coming when people will kill you thinking they’re actually doing a sacred service to \nd God\nd*,\wj*
\v 3 \wj but they’ll be doing these things because they don’t know either the father or me.\wj*
\v 4 \wj I’ve told you these things so that when they happen in the future, you’ll remember that I’ve already told you about them.\wj*
\s1 The work of God’s spirit
\p “\wj I didn’t tell you all of this right at the beginning because I was with you all,\wj*
\v 5 \wj but soon I’ll be returning to the one who sent me. Yet none of you are asking me where I’ll be going,\wj*
\v 6 \wj rather you are all just weighed down because I’ve told you these things.\wj*
\v 7 \wj But honestly it’s for your benefit that I will leave here, because if I don’t, then the assistant won’t be coming to you. But after I’ve gone, I’ll send him to you all.\wj*
\v 8 \wj When he comes, he’ll scold the world about sin and teach them about righteousness and judgement—\wj*
\v 9 \wj about sin because they don’t believe that I was sent by God,\wj*
\v 10 \wj about righteousness because I am going to the father and you won’t be able to see me any longer,\wj*
\v 11 \wj and about judgement because the ruler of this world has been judged.\wj*
\p
\v 12 “\wj I still have a lot to tell you all, but you’re not able to handle it all right now.\wj*
\v 13 \wj But when the assistant comes, the \nd spirit\nd* of truth, he will guide you in all truth because he won’t be speaking from his own thoughts, but will tell you what he’s been told, and he will explain to you what’s still going to happen.\wj*
\v 14 \wj He’ll be honouring me because he’ll take what is mine and will explain it to you all.\wj*
\v 15 \wj Everything that the father has is mine, that’s why I said he will take what is mine and explain it to you.\wj*
\s1 A brief upset coming followed by happiness
\p
\v 16 “\wj It won’t be much longer and you won’t be able to see me any more, and then a little while after that, and you’ll see me again.”\wj*
\p
\v 17 \wj This got his followers asking each other, “What’s all this about seeing him for not much longer, and then seeing him again after a while? And why does he say he’s going to the father?\wj*”
\v 18 So they were saying, “What’s this about ‘not much longer’? We don’t know what he means.”
\p
\v 19 However \nd Yeshua\nd* knew what they wanted to ask him, and so he said to them, “\wj You are trying to find out from each other what I meant when I said that you won’t be able to see me after a little while, and then a little while after that you’ll see me again.\wj*
\v 20 \wj I can assure you that you’ll be weeping and mourning but the world will be elated. You’ll be upset but then your upset will turn into happiness.\wj*
\v 21 \wj A woman giving birth has pains when the delivery begins, but when she hears that the baby is born, she doesn’t remember those pains any more because she’s so happy that her child was born.\wj*
\v 22 \wj So too with all of you: you’ll be upset for a while but then I’ll be with you again and you’ll be so happy and no one will be able to take that happiness away from you.\wj*
\p
\v 23 “\wj When that happens, you won’t be asking me for anything. I can assure you that whatever you request from the father in my name and my authority will be given to you.\wj*
\v 24 \wj Up until now you haven’t asked \add him\add* for anything using my authority, but after that time, you’ll be able to make requests and they’ll be answered so that your happiness will be complete.\wj*
\s1 A new era is coming very soon
\p
\v 25 “\wj So far I’ve told you these things in parables, however a time is coming when I’ll no longer be speaking in parables but will tell you things about the father quite plainly.\wj*
\v 26 \wj At that time you’ll have my authority to request from the father. I’m not saying that I’ll be asking him on your behalf,\wj*
\v 27 \wj no, because he himself loves you all because you have loved me and have believed that I was sent by \nd God\nd*.\wj*
\v 28 \wj I was sent out by the father and I have come into the world, but I’ll be leaving the world again and returning to the father.\wj*”
\p
\v 29 Yeshua’s followers responded, “Ah, now you’re speaking plainly and not using parables.
\v 30 Finally we realise that you know everything already and don’t need to ask anyone else, and so we now believe that you came from \nd God\nd*.”
\p
\v 31 “\wj So now you all believe?\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* answered.
\v 32 “\wj The time is coming and is here already when you will all be scattered in various directions and will leave me by myself, but I won’t be alone because the father is \add always\add* with me.\wj*
\v 33 \wj I’ve told you these things so that you can all have peace in me. You will have troubles in this world, but be courageous because I have overcome the world.\wj*”
\c 17
\s1 Yeshua prays for his current and future followers
\p
\v 1 After \nd Yeshua\nd* had finished speaking, he looked up to the sky and said, “\wj Father, it’s now the time for you to honour your son so that the son can honour you.\wj*
\v 2 \wj You already gave me authority over all people so that I could grant eternal life to everyone that you’ve given me.\wj*
\v 3 \wj And eternal life means knowing you, the only true \nd God\nd*, and knowing me—\nd Yeshua\nd* the \nd messiah\nd* that you sent.\wj*
\v 4 \wj I honoured you here on the earth by completing everything that you gave me to do.\wj*
\v 5 \wj So father, now you yourself can honour me with the greatness that I had when I was together with you before the creation of the world.\wj*
\p
\v 6 “\wj I revealed your power to the ones that you gave me from this world. They were yours and you gave them to me, and they have obeyed your teaching.\wj*
\v 7 \wj Now they understand that everything that you gave to me came from you,\wj*
\v 8 \wj because I passed on to them the messages that you gave to me, and they accepted them. Now they believe that I came from you and that it was you who sent me here.\wj*
\p
\v 9 “\wj I’m asking about \em them\em*. It’s not the people of this world that I’m asking about, but about the ones that you gave me because they belong to you.\wj*
\v 10 \wj Everything that’s mine is yours, and everything that’s your is mine, and I’ve been honoured by their actions.\wj*
\v 11 \wj I’m about to leave this world and come to you, but they will stay here in it. Holy father, use your power to keep protect the ones that you gave me, so that they might be united just like you and I are one.\wj*
\v 12 \x + \xo 17:12: \xt Psa 41:9; Yhn 13:18.\x*\wj When I was with them, I protected them with the authority that you gave, and I guarded them so that not one of them perished, except the one who chose destruction so that it will indeed happen as the scriptures foretold.\wj*
\v 13 \wj But soon I’ll be coming to you, and I’m speaking these things in the world so that they will have the same happiness as me and be fulfilled in their lives.\wj*
\v 14 \wj I’ve passed on your teaching to them, and the world hated them because they don’t belong to this world, just as I don’t.\wj*
\v 15 \wj I’m not asking you to remove them out of this world, but rather to stop evil from overcoming them.\wj*
\v 16 \wj They don’t belong to this world just as I don’t.\wj*
\v 17 \wj Purify them with the truth—your message is that truth.\wj*
\v 18 \wj In the same way that you sent me out into this world, so I also send them out into the world.\wj*
\v 19 \wj I’m purifying myself for their sakes so that they also may be made pure by the truth.\wj*
\p
\v 20 “\wj But it’s not just on behalf of the ones right here that I’m asking, but also for all the others who will believe that I came from you when they hear the message of these ones,\wj*
\v 21 \wj so that they will all become united, just as you, father, are in me and I am in you. I ask that they will also be in us so that the world will be able to believe that it was you who sent me here.\wj*
\v 22 \wj And the honour that you’ve given me, I’ve passed on to them so that they can be united just as we are one—\wj*
\v 23 \wj me in them and you in me so that they can be perfected as one. Then the world will know that you sent me here and that you love them \add just\add* like you love me.\wj*
\p
\v 24 \wj Father, I want those that you’ve given me to be with me wherever I am so that they’ll be able to see my greatness—the greatness that you gave me because you loved me even before the creation of the world.\wj*
\v 25 \wj Righteous father, this world didn’t know you, but I know you and these ones know that you sent me here.\wj*
\v 26 \wj I revealed your power and authority to them and will continue to do so, so that the love that you love me with might be in them, and I too might be in them.\wj*”
\c 18
\s1 Yeshua is arrested
\r (Mat. 26:47-56; Mark 14:43-50; Luke 22:47-53)
\p
\v 1 After he’d said all this, \nd Yeshua\nd* and his followers went out of Yerushalem \add proper\add* and over the Kidron stream towards a garden that he and his followers entered.
\v 2 And Yudas (the one who would hand him over) also knew the place because \nd Yeshua\nd* and his followers often met there.
\v 3 Meanwhile Yudas had met with the soldiers and servants of the chief priests and the Pharisee party, and they all started coming into the garden with lanterns and flaming torches and weapons.
\v 4 \nd Yeshua\nd* who already knew what was going to happen to him, came forward and asked them, “\wj Who are you all looking for?\wj*”
\p
\v 5 And they answered, “Yeshua—the one from \nd Nazareth\nd*.”
\p Yeshua responded, “\wj \em I am\em* the one.\wj*”
\p Yudas, the one handing him over, was standing there among them.
\v 6 But when Yeshua had said that he is the one, they backed away and fell to the ground.\f + \fr 18:6 \ft TD: It’s not clear from the original if they fell over backwards, or if they stepped back and then fell forward (either voluntarily or involuntarily) onto their knees.\f*
\v 7 So he asked them again, “\wj Who are you all looking for?\wj*”
\p And they answered, “\nd Yeshua\nd*—the one from \nd Nazareth\nd*.”
\p
\v 8 \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “\wj I already told you all that \em I am\em* the one. So if it’s me that you’re looking for, let these others leave.\wj*”
\v 9 (In this way, the statement was fulfilled that Yeshua had said previously: ‘I didn’t lose any of the ones that you gave me.’)\f + \fr 18:9 \ft TD: It’s not certain from the original whether v9 was part of Mark’s commentary on the events or part of Yeshua’s response to the arresting party.\f*
\p
\v 10 Then Simon Peter drew the sword that he was carrying and swiped at the servant of the high priest, cutting off his right ear. The servant’s name was Malchus.
\v 11 \x + \xo 18:11: \xt Mat 26:39; Mrk 14:36; Luk 22:42.\x*But \nd Yeshua\nd* said to Peter, “\wj Put your sword back in its sheath. I need to proceed with the plan that the father has prepared for me—I can’t just avoid the suffering.\wj*”
\s1 Yeshua is taken to Annas
\p
\v 12 So the soldiers and their commander, and the servants of the Jewish leaders arrested \nd Yeshua\nd* and tied him up.
\v 13 First they took him to Annas, the father-in-law of Caiaphas who was the chief priest that year.
\v 14 \x + \xo 18:14: \xt Yhn 11:49-50.\x*(Caiaphas was the one who had suggested that it was better for the people and the nation if \em one\em* man should die for \add all of\add* them.)
\s1 Peter denies being a Yeshua-follower
\r (Mat. 26:59-66; Mark 14:55-64; Luke 22:66-71)
\p
\v 15 Now Simon Peter and another intern were following Yeshua, and since that other intern was known to the chief priest, he was allowed to enter following Yeshua into the courtyard of the chief priest
\v 16 while Peter waited outside at the door. Then the other intern who was known to the chief priest went back and spoke to the woman at the door and brought Peter in too.
\v 17 But the servant girl who was watching the door challenged Peter, “Aren’t you also one of the followers of that man?”
\p “No, I’m not,” he responded.
\p
\v 18 Meanwhile the servants and attendants had made a fire and were standing around it warming themselves, and Peter also went and stood there to warm himself.
\s1 Annas tries to interrogate Yeshua
\r (Mat. 26:59-66; Mark 14:69-72; Luke 22:58-62)
\p
\v 19 Now the chief priest interrogated \nd Yeshua\nd* about his followers and about his teaching.
\v 20 \nd Yeshua\nd* answered him, “I’ve spoken openly to the people. I always taught in the meeting halls and in the temple where Jewish people meet. I didn’t speak in secret
\v 21 so why are you asking \em me\em*? Ask the people who heard what I told them—they’re the ones who know what I said.”
\p
\v 22 When he said that, one of the attendants standing there slapped \nd Yeshua\nd* \add on the face\add* and said, “You think you can answer the chief priest like that?”
\p
\v 23 But \nd Yeshua\nd* responded, “If I said anything wrong, tell me my error. But if it was true, why are you hitting me?”
\p
\v 24 So Annas sent him away, still tied up, to Caiaphas the chief priest.
\s1 Peter again denies following Yeshua
\r (Mat. 26:71-75; Mark 14:69-72; Luke 22:58-62)
\p
\v 25 Simon Peter was still standing by the fire warming himself when he was asked, “Aren’t you also one of his followers?”
\p But he denied it, saying, “No, I’m not.”
\p
\v 26 One of the servants of the chief priest who was a relative of the man whose ear Peter had cut off said, “Didn’t I see you in the garden with that Yeshua?”
\p
\v 27 But Peter again denied it, and just then a rooster crowed.
\s1 Pilate interrogates Yeshua
\r (Mat. 26:71-75; Mark 14:69-72; Luke 22:58-62)
\p
\v 28 Then they led \nd Yeshua\nd* out from Caiaphas’ place and towards the residence of the governor. It was now the early hours of the morning and as Jews, they didn’t enter the residence of the Roman governor so they wouldn’t become defiled and thus unable to eat the Passover meal.
\v 29 So Governor Pilate came outside to them and asked, “What charge are you all bringing against this man?”
\p
\v 30 “We wouldn’t have brought him to you if he hadn’t committed a serious crime,” they answered.
\p
\v 31 So Pilate said, “You just take him and judge him yourselves according to your own laws.”
\p But the Jewish leaders responded, “We don’t have permission to execute anyone.”
\v 32 (This happened to fulfil what \nd Yeshua\nd* had said\x + \xo 18:32: \xt Yhn 3:14; 12:32.\x* about the way that he was going to die.)
\p
\v 33 So Pilate went back into his governor’s residence and called for \nd Yeshua\nd* and asked him, “So you’re the king of the Jews?”
\p
\v 34 “\wj Are you saying this yourself,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* asked, “\wj or did others say it about me?\wj*”
\p
\v 35 Pilate retorted, “Hoy! I’m not a Jew. It was your own people and the chief priests that handed you over to me. What have you done?”
\p
\v 36 “\wj My kingdom isn’t in this world,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj because if it was, my supporters would have fought so that I wouldn’t have been handed over to the Jewish leaders. But no, my kingdom isn’t from here.\wj*”
\p
\v 37 “So you \em are\em* a king then?” Pilate responded.
\p “\wj You’re saying that I’m a king,\wj*” said \nd Yeshua\nd*, “\wj and indeed I was born to be a king. I came into the world so that I could testify to the truth.\wj*”
\p
\v 38 “\add Yeah.\add* What is truth?” said Pilate.
\s1 Pilate gives permission to execute an innocent man
\r (Mat. 27:15-31; Mark 15:6-20; Luke 23:13-25)
\p After he’d said this, Pilate went back outside to the Jews and told them, “I can’t find anything that he’s guilty of.
\v 39 But you all have a custom here that the governor can release one prisoner during the Passover. So would you like me to release the king of the Jews?”
\p
\v 40 But they all yelled back, “No, not this one. Release Barabbas.” (Barabbas was a robber.)
\c 19
\p
\v 1 So Pilate took \nd Yeshua\nd* and had him flogged.
\v 2 Then the soldiers twisted some thorn branches together into a crown and put it on Yeshua’s head, and they dressed him in a \add royal\add* purple robe.
\v 3 They came up to him and said, “Greetings, you king of the Jews,” and then slapped him.
\p
\v 4 Then Pilate went back outside and said to the Jews, “Look here. I’m bringing him out to you so that you all can know that I didn’t find him guilty of anything.”
\v 5 So they led \nd Yeshua\nd* out wearing the thorny crown and the kingly robe, and Pilate said, “Look. Here’s the man.”
\p
\v 6 Now when the chief priests and their supporters saw him, they yelled out, “Execute him on a stake! Execute him on a stake!”
\p “Well you take him and execute him on a stake,” Pilate answered, “because I haven’t found anything that he’s guilty of.”
\p
\v 7 The Jews responded, “We have a law and he should be executed according to that law because he said he was the son of \nd God\nd*.”
\p
\v 8 Now when Pilate heard that, he became more afraid.
\v 9 So he went back inside the residence and asked Yeshua, “Where do you come from?”
\p But Yeshua didn’t answer him.
\v 10 So Pilate said, “Why don’t you answer me? Don’t you realise that I have the authority to release you and I also have the authority to have you executed on a stake?”
\p
\v 11 “\wj You have no authority over me,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* answered, “\wj none at all, except what has been granted to you from above. Because of this, the sin of the person who handed me over to you is greater.\wj*”
\p
\v 12 After hearing this, Pilate wanted to release him but the Jews yelled out, “If you release that man, you’re no friend of Caesar. Everyone who claims to be a king is no friend of Caesar’s.”
\p
\v 13 So now Pilate, having heard all this, brought \nd Yeshua\nd* outside \add again\add*. Pilate sat down on the judge’s seat at a place called The Stone Pavement (and called Gabbatha in Hebrew).
\v 14 It was now about noon on the day when the Passover meal is prepared, and Pilate said to the Jews, “Look. Here’s your king.”
\p
\v 15 They yelled back, “Take him away. Take him away. Execute him on a stake.”
\p Pilate asked them, “You want me to have your king executed on a stake?”
\p “We don’t have any king other than Caesar,” the chief priests answered.
\p
\v 16 So Pilate gave them his permission and handed \nd Yeshua\nd* over to them, and they took him away to be executed on a stake.
\s1 Yeshua is hung on a stake
\r (Mat. 27:32-44; Mark 15:21-32; Luke 23:26-43)
\p
\v 17 Carrying the pole\f + \fr 19:17 \ft TD: The Greek word used here is used in other places to mean a stake such as used to make a fence. It’s uncertain whether or not it had a horizontal cross-piece, although the Romans did use a range of methods.\f* himself, Yeshua arrived at the Place of the Skull (called Golgotha in Hebrew) just out of the city
\v 18 where they secured him to a stake along with two others—one stake on each side and with \nd Yeshua\nd* on the middle one.
\v 19 Pilate wrote out a title and put it on the stake: \nd Yeshua\nd* from \nd Nazareth\nd*, the king of the Jews.
\v 20 Many Jews read this title because the place where \nd Yeshua\nd* was executed was near the city, and it had been written in Hebrew, Latin, and Greek.
\v 21 But the Jewish chief priests complained to Pilate, “Don’t write ‘The king of the Jews’, but rather ‘The one who \em said\em* he was king of the Jews’.”
\p
\v 22 However Pilate answered, “What I’ve written, I’ve written.”
\p
\v 23 After the soldiers had fastened \nd Yeshua\nd* to the stake, they took his clothes and placed in four piles, one for each of them. This left his robe, which had been woven from top to bottom in one piece.
\v 24 So they said to each other, “Rather than tearing this, let’s throw a dice to see who will get it.” (This fulfilled what was written in the scriptures\x + \xo 19:24: \xt Psa 22:18.\x* that said: they divided my garments among themselves and threw a dice for my clothes.) So they went ahead and did that.
\p
\v 25 Meanwhile a group of women had stayed standing near \nd Yeshua\nd* on the stake: his mother and his aunt, Maria the wife of Clopas, and Maria from Magdala.
\v 26 When \nd Yeshua\nd* saw his mother and also the intern that he loved standing nearby, he said to her, “\wj Look, he’ll be your son.\wj*”
\v 27 And to the intern he said, “\wj Look, she’ll be your mother.\wj*” And that intern took her into his own \add home\add* from then on.
\s1 Yeshua gives up his life on the stake
\r (Mat. 27:45-56; Mark 15:33-41; Luke 23:44-49)
\p
\v 28 Having done this, \nd Yeshua\nd* knew that everything had been accomplished, and (in order for the scriptures\x + \xo 19:28: \xt Psa 69:21; 22:15.\x* to be fulfilled) said, “\wj I’m thirsty.\wj*”
\p
\v 29 There was a container lying there full of vinegary wine, so they placed a sponge on a hyssop stalk, soaked it in the wine, and held it up to his mouth.
\v 30 After \nd Yeshua\nd* had sucked some wine out, he said, “\wj It is finished.\wj*” Then he bowed his head and gave up his spirit.
\s1 Yeshua’s side is pierced with a spear
\p
\v 31 Now because it was the preparation day\x + \xo 19:31: \xt Yhn 19:14.\x* for the coming Rest Day, the Jews didn’t want the bodies to remain on the stakes after dusk (because it was even a special Rest Day.) So they asked Pilate to command for their legs to be broken \add to hasten their deaths\add* and then they could be taken down \add sooner\add*.
\v 32 So the soldiers came and broke the legs of the men on each side of Yeshua,
\v 33 but when they got to him, they saw that he was already dead so they didn’t break his legs.
\v 34 Instead one of the soldiers stabbed his side with a spear and immediately blood and water came out.
\v 35 The one who actually saw this happen\f + \fr 9:35 \ft Believed to be the author of this account.\f* has testified this and his account is accurate so that you \add readers\add* can also believe it,
\v 36 because these things also happened to fulfil what was written in the scriptures,\x + \xo 19:36: \xt Exo 12:46; Num 9:12; Psa 34:20.\x* that ‘none of his bones will be broken,’
\v 37 and in another place,\x + \xo 19:37: \xt Zech 12:10; Rev 1:7.\x* ‘they will look at the one that they pierced.’
\s1 The wrapping and laying of Yeshua’s body
\r (Mat. 27:57-61; Mark 15:42-47; Luke 23:50-56)
\p
\v 38 After all of this, Yosef from Arimathea went to Pilate. (Yosef was a follower of Yeshua, but secretly because he was afraid of what the Jewish leaders might do.) He asked Pilate for permission to remove \nd Yeshua’s\nd* body, and it was granted to him so they went and got his body.
\v 39 \x + \xo 19:39: \xt Yhn 3:1-2.\x*Nicodemus (the one who had first visited Yeshua at night) also came, bringing around 30kg of burial spices.
\v 40 So they took \nd Yeshua’s\nd* body and wrapped it around with linen strips with the spices as per the Jewish burial customs.
\v 41 There was a garden out at the place where Yeshua had been executed, and in the garden there was a new tomb that hadn’t been used yet.
\v 42 So because it was the preparation day and because the tomb was nearby, they laid his body in there.
\c 20
\s1 The body is missing from the chamber
\r (Mat. 28:1-8; Mark 16:1-8; Luke 24:1-12)
\p
\v 1 The following Sunday, Maria from Magdala went out to the tomb very early when it was still dark, and she saw that the stone had been removed from the entrance.
\v 2 So she ran quickly and went to Simon Peter and the other intern that \nd Yeshua\nd* loved, and told them, “They’ve taken the \nd master’s\nd* body out of the tomb and we don’t know where they’ve put it.”
\p
\v 3 So Peter and the other intern went out to the tomb.
\v 4 They were running together, but the other intern was a bit faster than Peter and so he got to the tomb first.
\v 5 Without going in, he stooped down at the entrance and looked in and saw the linen strips lying there.
\v 6 But Peter came along behind him and went straight into the tomb and also saw the linen strips lying there.
\v 7 But the piece of cloth that had been on the head wasn’t lying there with the linen strips, but had been folded and placed separately.
\v 8 So now the other intern who had arrived first also went inside and he saw it all and believed \add that Yeshua had risen\add*.
\v 9 (At that time they weren’t yet aware of the scripture about him coming back to life.)
\v 10 So they went back again to their homes.
\s1 Yeshua reveals himself to Maria from Magdala
\r (Mat. 28:9-10; Mark 16:9-11)
\p
\v 11 But Maria had stayed there outside the tomb weeping. But when she stooped down and looked into the tomb,
\v 12 she saw two messengers dressed in white sitting there—one at the head end and one at the feet end of the slab where \nd Yeshua’s\nd* body had been lying.
\v 13 They spoke to her, “Woman, why are you crying?”
\p “Because they’ve taken away my \nd master\nd*,” she replied, “and I don’t know where they’ve put him.”
\p
\v 14 \nd Then\nd* she turned back around and saw \nd Yeshua\nd* standing there, but she didn’t realise who it was.
\v 15 \nd Yeshua\nd* asked her, “\wj Woman, why are you crying? Who are you looking for?\wj*”
\p Maria assumed he might be the gardener, so she answered, “Mister, if you took the body, tell me where you put it and I’ll get it taken away \add for you\add*.”
\p
\v 16 \nd Yeshua\nd* just answered, “\wj Maria.\wj*”
\p She spun around and said, “My teacher!” (‘Rabboni’ in Hebrew.)
\p
\v 17 “\wj Don’t touch me,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* said to her, “\wj because I haven’t gone back up to the father yet, but go and tell my brothers that I’m going up to my father and the father of you all, and my god and the god of you all.\wj*”
\p
\v 18 So Maria went and told the trainees, “I’ve seen the \nd master\nd*,” and she told them what he’d said.
\s1 Yeshua appears to his followers
\r (Mat. 28:16-20; Mark 16:14-18; Luke 24:36-49)
\p
\v 19 On Sunday evening \nd Yeshua’s\nd* trainees had met together and had the doors locked because they were afraid of the Jewish leaders, but Yeshua arrived and stood in the middle of the room and said, “Peace to you all.”
\v 20 Then he showed them his hands and his side and they were so happy now that they had seen the \nd master\nd*.
\v 21 \nd Yeshua\nd* continued, “\wj Peace to you all. Now I am sending you all out just like the father sent me out.\wj*”
\v 22 Then he breathed on them and said, “\wj Receive the holy \nd spirit\nd*.\wj*
\v 23 \x + \xo 20:23: \xt Mat 16:19; 18:18.\x*\wj If you forgive anyone’s sins, then they’ll be forgiven but if you withhold forgiveness, then it will be withheld.\wj*”
\s1 Thomas sees the evidence for himself
\p
\v 24 But Thomas, one of the twelve (nicknamed ‘Twin’), wasn’t with them when \nd Yeshua\nd* had come
\v 25 so the other trainees told him, “We have seen the \nd master\nd*.”
\p But he replied, “I won’t believe that unless I see the mark of the nails in his hands and I can put my finger into the marks and can put my hand into \add the gash on\add* his side.”
\p
\v 26 Eight days later, \nd Yeshua’s\nd* trainees were again together inside, and \add this time\add* Thomas was with them.
\v 27 Yeshua came and stood in the middle of the room even though the doors were shut, and said, “\wj Peace to you all.\wj*”
\p
\v 28 Thomas spoke up, “My \nd master\nd* and my \nd god\nd*!”
\p
\v 29 “\wj So you believe now because you’ve seen me,\wj*” said \nd Yeshua\nd*. “\wj The ones who haven’t seen me, but who believe anyway, will \add certainly\add* be rewarded.\wj*”
\s1 Why this document was written
\p
\v 30 \nd Yeshua\nd* went on to do many other miracles in front of his trainees which aren’t recorded in this account.
\v 31 But what has been written here has been recorded so that you might all believe that \nd Yeshua\nd* is the \nd messiah\nd*, God’s son, and then by believing, so that you might have \add true\add* life through his power.
\c 21
\s1 The miracle of the net full of fish
\p
\v 1 After all this, \nd Yeshua\nd* revealed himself again to his trainees at Lake Galilee. It happened like this:
\v 2 Simon Peter, Thomas nicknamed ‘Twin’, \nd Nathanael\nd* from Cana in Galilee, the sons of Zebedee, and two other trainees had gathered together
\v 3 \x + \xo 21:3: \xt Luk 5:5.\x*when Simon Peter said that he was going fishing and the others said that they’d join him.
\p So they went off and got in the boat, but they didn’t catch anything that night.
\p
\v 4 \nd When\nd* the dawn was approaching, \nd Yeshua\nd* was standing there on the shore, but they didn’t know that it was him.
\v 5 He called out, “\wj Hey, young fellas. Don’t you have any fish?\wj*”
\p “None.” they answered.
\p
\v 6 \x + \xo 21:6: \xt Luk 5:6.\x*Then he said, “\wj Throw the net out over the right side of the boat and you’ll find some.\wj*” So they did it and they caught so many fish that the net was too heavy to pull back in.
\p
\v 7 Now the intern that \nd Yeshua\nd* loved said to Peter, “It’s the master!” When Simon Peter heard that, he put on his robe (because he didn’t have it on), and jumped overboard into the lake.
\v 8 The other trainees followed in the little boat dragging the net behind them because they were only about 100m out from the shore.
\v 9 When they went up the beach, they saw some bread there and a charcoal fire with fish cooking on it
\v 10 and \nd Yeshua\nd* told them, “\wj Bring some of the fish that you just caught.\wj*”
\p
\v 11 So Simon Peter went and dragged the net up onto the beach. Amazingly it hadn’t torn even though it contained 153 large fish.
\v 12 Then \nd Yeshua\nd* said, “\wj Now, come and have breakfast.\wj*” But none of the trainees dared to ask who he was, because they figured it must be the \nd master\nd*.
\v 13 \nd Yeshua\nd* brought the bread to them and shared it around, and then likewise for the fish.
\p
\v 14 This was now the third time that \nd Yeshua\nd* had appeared to his trainees since he’d come back to life.
\s1 Yeshua questions Peter
\p
\v 15 While they were eating, Yeshua asked Simon Peter, “\wj Simon, son of Yohan, do you love me more than these?\wj*”
\p Peter answered, “Yes, \nd master\nd*, you know that I love you.”
\p Yeshua responded, “\wj Feed my lambs.\wj*”
\v 16 Then he asked again, “\wj Simon, son of Yohan, do you love me?\wj*”
\p Peter replied, “Yes, \nd master\nd*, you know that I love you.”
\p Yeshua responded, “\wj Shepherd my sheep.\wj*”
\v 17 Then he asked a third time, “\wj Simon, son of Yohan, do you love me?\wj*”
\p Peter was now upset that he had been asked a third time if he loved him, and he answered, “\nd Master\nd*, you know everything.”
\p “\wj Feed my sheep,\wj*” \nd Yeshua\nd* responded.
\v 18 “\wj I can assure you that while you are young, you dress yourself and go wherever you want to go, but as you age, you’ll be stretching out your hands and others will dress you and will take you where you don’t want to go.\wj*”
\v 19 When he said this, Yeshua was indicating how Peter would die honouring \nd God\nd*, and he told Peter, “Keep following me.”
\p
\v 20 \x + \xo 21:20: \xt Yhn 13:25.\x*When Peter turned around he saw that the intern that Yeshua loved was following them—the one who had leaned on \nd Yeshua’s\nd* chest during the supper and asked who the one was who would turn Yeshua over.
\v 21 Noticing him, Peter asked \nd Yeshua\nd*, “\nd Master\nd*, what about that one?”
\p
\v 22 But \nd Yeshua\nd* replied, “\wj If I want him to stay alive until I come back, what business would it be of yours? You just stay following me.\wj*”
\p
\v 23 As a result of that, a rumour went around the others that that one would not die, but \nd Yeshua\nd* never said that. (He only said, “If I want him to stay alive until I come back, what business would it be of yours?”)
\s1 Statement of fact
\p
\v 24 This author is the intern that testifies about these things—the one who wrote this down and whose account is true.
\v 25 (There were also many other things that \nd Yeshua\nd* did, which if they were all written down then even the world itself wouldn’t have room for all the books that would need to be written.)
